<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Weighs Nuclear Option as Speculations Arise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Speculations have already begun
to arise as Pakistan is still weighing its options very carefully
several days after India exploded its nuclear devices.
</P>
<P>
In a one-sentence statement released here Sunday afternoon, a
spokesman from the Pakistani Foreign Office firmly denied reports
that his country conducted a nuclear test earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
"This is a motivated rumor," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after a Western news agency Sunday reported
that German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, "quoting reliable
information," said in Birmingham, England, that Pakistan had
carried out a nuclear test.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has
been under mounting domestic pressure to make a "matching
response" to India's testing on Monday and again Wednesday of five
nuclear devices.
</P>
<P>
The Sharif government has been keeping its options open over
how to respond to India's tests while strongly condemning the
Indian action as a "provocative defiance of international opinion
and an immediate and grave threat to Pakistan's security." It has
been also urging the international community to impose severe
punitive sanctions on India.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a party workers meeting Sunday in Lahore, about 300
kilometers east of here, Sharif however made it clear that
Pakistan possesses nuclear capability and it can go nuclear
"within 12 to 24 hours."
</P>
<P>
"We have not taken any decision in haste in this regard and we
are monitoring the sharp reaction of the world toward the Indian
nuclear explosion," he said while reaffirming the solemn pledge
not to compromise national security at all for any monetary gains.
</P>
<P>
He said India, in view of its internal political instability,
conducted nuclear tests to establish supremacy and to make some
political gains in the next general elections.
</P>
<P>
"We are studying the international scenario carefully and
taking into account the situation judiciously arising as a result
of Indian nuclear tests," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some big powers including the United States and
Japan have been urging Pakistan to exercise restraint and not to
follow India's suit.
</P>
<P>
The United States sent a high-caliber delegation, led by Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, to Pakistan on Friday in a bid
to woo Pakistan away from a nuclear option.
</P>
<P>
Special Envoy of Japanese Prime Minister Hashimoto, Seiichiro
Noboru, also arrived here on Sunday to urge Pakistan to show
restraint in response to India's tests.
</P>
<P>
Within hours of the U.S. delegation's departure from here
Saturday, Pakistan's Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad ruled out
the possibility of giving up the nuclear option and vowed that it
would not submit to any brow-beating.
</P>
<P>
"Why are you trying to dissuade us from an option which is of
vital national interest for us," Shamshad said while responding to
a Western journalist.
</P>
<P>
However, he said his country has assured Washington that it
would not act in haste and its final decision will be driven by
its supreme national interests and the scope of the threat posed
to its security.
</P>
<P>
"Our response will be well-considered, mature, sober and
comprehensive," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
