<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Parties Apply for Postponement of Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- In a dramatic turn in the run-up
to the Lesotho general elections, the country's three main political
parties have demanded a postponement of the election because of
alleged irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Basotholand Congress Party, opposition Basotho National
Party and the Marematlou Freedom Party, have lodged an urgent
application in the Lesotho High Court asking for the postponement,
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not say when the application was filed.
</P>
<P>
The parties asked the court to put off the polls, due to be held on
May 23, to enable the Independent Electoral Commission (IEC) to
investigate the alleged irregularities.
</P>
<P>
According to papers filed in the high court, one of the alleged
irregularities is that about 80 percent of voters in one village were
registered as having been born on a New Year's day.
</P>
<P>
The three parties said that the IEC had not allowed political
parties sufficient time to examine the final voters' list.
</P>
<P>
The case will be argued in the high court on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of Basotho converged in Maseru on Sunday to
attend the final election rallies organized by the main parties.
</P>
<P>
The commomwealth secretariat in London has sent a special team of
observers to monitor the election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
