<HEADLINE> Museveni, Nguesso Hold Talks on African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
and President of the Republic of Congo, Sassou Nguesso, held
talks here Sunday evening on bilateral economic cooperation
and African integration.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, which were held in the State House, the two
leaders discussed ways of actualizing the real integration of
Africa and stressed the vital necessity of building
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Museveni noted that one of the bottlenecks in creating
integration in Africa is the lack of physical linkages across the
continent.
</P>
<P>
Despite the signing of the African common market treaty in
Abuja some years ago, Africa still lacks road, rail and air
linkages without which the common market cannot become a reality.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said Uganda is opposed to diving Africa into
Francophone and Anglophone groupings, adding that Africa's
historical links with Europe should be used to make more contacts
for Africa but must not be allowed to divide the African people
permanently.
</P>
<P>
Nguesso, who arrived here Sunday, said his country's present
leadership is totally committed to promoting regional bodies that
will advance African integration.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to cooperate in economic field and as a
first step, to exchange business delegations to explore business
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
They also promised to strengthen air connections between the
two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
