<HEADLINE> Iraq Says Oil Sector's Recovery Depends on Getting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has said its oil sector can
restore the production and export capacity to the 1990 level in
just six months if getting the spare parts for the defunct
machines.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Planning and Study Department at the Oil
Ministry, Falih Hassan al-Khayat was quoted by Iraqi News Agency
as saying Sunday that Iraq can produce 2.56 million barrels of
crude oil on a daily basis, of which 2 million for export -- two
months after the arrival of basic equipments Iraq has applied for
to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has not decided yet on the Iraqi
recommendations included in the report of the technical team sent
by the U.N. Secretary-General to Baghdad in mid-March to evaluate
Iraq's oil production and export capacity.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil production and export capacity has been much
undermined by the lack of spare parts of machines and basic
equipments as the result of the 1990 imposition of U.N. sanctions
for the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, however, is allowed to sell 5.2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of oil every six months for buying back food and medicine
for its suffering people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
