<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Economic Summit Opens in Namibia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Southern African heads of
state began flying into Namibian capital Windhoek Sunday
afternoon to attend the Southern African economic summit due to
be opened later on the day.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 senior government officials and 650 business
leaders are expected to attend the three-day conference aimed at
promoting regional cooperation and policy integration, the South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The summit, now an annual event, is jointly organized by the
World Economic Forum (WEF) and the Southern African Development
Community (SADC), a 14-nation trading bloc.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be opened by Namibian President Sam Nujoma, is
expected to be a major marketing opportunity for the SADC, seen
as the most promising economic grouping on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the meeting include South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki, Democratic Republic of Congo President
Laurent Kabila, Zambian President Fredrick Chiluba, Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe and Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano.
</P>
<P>
They will be joined by several hundred delegates, including
senior executives of some of the world's largest corporations.
</P>
<P>
WEF's Director, Fredrick Sicre, said Sunday that representatives
from 60 countries will discuss closer cooperation between
southern Africa and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Victor Moll, Managing Director of Standard Bank in Namibia,
said that the business sectors of southern African countries
need to cooperate more closely.
</P>
<P>
He said that a proposal is under discussion to form a SADC
business council, which will get businesses to work together to
exploit the region's competitive advantages.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also deal with the seven so-called
development corridors in the region -- bordering areas of
neighboring countries which have high potential to attract
investment and are jointly developed by the neighboring
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
