<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Refutes Ankara's Territory Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq warned Ankara on Sunday
against Turkey's territory claims to the northern Iraqi city of
Mosul, cautioning that it would cost Turkey its relations with
Iraq and other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman said that if Turkey made such a
claim, Iraq could also reclaim many territories now part of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was commenting on remarks of Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel in a symposium at War Academy in Istanbul that
Mosul is part of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Turkish president's remarks came at a
time Iraq underlined its good-willed policy towards Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish president, to the astonishment of Iraq, has made
such remarks which are inconsistent with the said principles or
with historical facts," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"With full confidence, we can say that the Iraqi territory,
called the Provincial State of Mosul during the Ottoman rule, had
enjoyed historical position well-known throughout Iraqi
civilizations," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"Raising such a issue could trigger wider relevant questions
of which Turkey would turn out a loser," warned the spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
