<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G8 Summit Ends with Birmingham Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Eight (G8) summit
ended here Sunday afternoon with the Birmingham Communique, urging
the benefits of the globalization be widely spread in a bid to
improve the people's quality of life across the world.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the United States, Germany, France, Italy, Japan,
Canada, Britain and Russia said in the communique that they must
ensure "their institutions and structures keep pace with the rapid
technological and economic changes under way in the world".
</P>
<P>
The overall global economic prospects remain good despite of
the temporary influence of the Asian financial crisis, which has
swept across some Asian countries since last July, the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
"We confirm our strong support for the efforts to re-establish
stability and growth in the region for the key role of the
International Financial Institutions," the document said, adding
"successful recovery in Asia " will bring important benefits to
all the countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and French President Jacques
Chirac both paid tribute to the Chinese government for promising
not to devaluate the Chinese currency, a decisive factor in
stabilizing the Asian and global financial markets.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the serious problem of unemployment and social
exclusion, the G8 leaders recognized "the importance of
modernizing domestic economic and social structures within a sound
macro-economic framework."
</P>
<P>
In particular, they have agreed to implement the following
measures in resolving the problem:
</P>
<P>
-- measures to keep young, long-term unemployed and other
groups hard hit by the unemployment find work;
</P>
<P>
-- measures to help entrepreneurs to set up companies;
</P>
<P>
-- carrying out structural reforms, including tax and benefit
systems more employment friendly and liberalisation of products
markets;
</P>
<P>
-- measures to promote lifelong learning.
</P>
<P>
The G8 countries also decided to enhance transnational
cooperation in fighting against various kinds of international
crimes, including drugs and weapons trafficking, smuggling of human
beings, the abuse of new technologies to steal and money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day conference, the leaders also discussed the
Indian nuclear tests, Middle East and Northern Ireland peace
process, Kosovo and the situation in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In a separate statement issued Friday, the G8 leaders strongly
condemned the Indian nuclear tests despite consistent
international opposition, calling on the New Delhi government to
stick to international agreements on comprehensively banning
nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
Under the final communique, the next G8 summit is to be held in
Koln, Germany on June 18-20 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
