<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Polio Eradication to Get Huge Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Rotary International, the global
non-governmental organization, has committed 304 million U.S.
Dollars for worldwide polio eradication, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 86 million Dollars will be used for the
eradication in Africa, the report said, quoting the "Current
Facts and Figures" issued by the club.
</P>
<P>
According to the bulletin, 119 nations have benefited from
grants for polio immunization and eradication efforts while over
one billion children have received oral polio vaccine from 1985
to 1996 and are successfully protected from polio.
</P>
<P>
"Today, as many as four million children who might have been
polio victims are walking and playing normally," the fact sheet
states, adding "more than 500,000 cases of polio are prevented
each year."
</P>
<P>
It says that 154 countries reported zero cases as of 1996
while in the same year, there might have about 40,000 cases.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 alone, more than 400 million children in 82 countries
received oral polio vaccine during national immunization days,
representing 60 percent of all the world's children under the age
of five.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the club, the World Health Organization, the United
Nations Children's Fund and the Center for Disease Control in the
United States, as well as governments of individual countries,
are contributors to the eradication effort which has set its
target for the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
