<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for Arab Efforts in Lifting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed
al-Sahhaf Sunday called for strengthening Arab solidarity and
enhancing joint Arab efforts to lift the U.N. embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, the Iraqi minister said the
resumption of Arab common action would be helpful not only for
Iraq but also for all the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that relations between Iraq and the rest of the Arab
Gulf nations, particularly Oman, Qatar, the United Arab Emirates
and Bahrain, are improving.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has proposed that Saudi Arabia and Iraq each set up an
interest office in the other's capital, al-Sahhaf added.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that Baghdad will continue to work with the
U.N. Security Council and the U.N. Special Commission on
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, with a view to
lifting the embargo.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the embargo is "a strategic mistake"
because it is impossible to isolate Iraq from the international
community, especially from the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister went on to say that the aim of the current
Iraqi diplomatic move is to make clear that his country has met
all its obligations, thereby the embargo should be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the reported Iraq-U.S. dialog, al-Sahhaf said "we
believe that dialog is the right way to solve problems," adding
that "however, we are not running after it with the United
States," he added.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay here, al-Sahhaf met Tunisian
President Zine Al-Abidine Ben Ali and conveyed him a message from
his Iraqi counterpart Saddam Hussein on the situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the Iraqi minister to Tunisia is part of Iraq's
diplomatic move to lobby support from Arab, African, European,
Asian and Latin American countries for lifting the embargo which
was imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf left here Sunday afternoon for Kenya to continue his
Arab and African tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
