<HEADLINE> Lesotho Polls Organizers Slate Opposition Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's Independent
Electoral Commission (IEC) said Sunday it was sad that three main
opposition parties demanded a court order to postpone the
forthcoming general election.
</P>
<P>
"Their action is terrible because it's going to dampen the
spirit prevailing amongst the Basotho nation... an atmosphere
conducive for elections," South African Press Association (SAPA)
quoted IEC's Chairman Sekara Mafisa as saying.
</P>
<P>
The timing of the court action was wrong and very drastic,
Mafisa said.
</P>
<P>
The election will be held on May 23 in the tiny mountain
kingdom, the country's third democratic election since its
independence in 1966.
</P>
<P>
The Basotholand Congress Party, Basotho National Party and the
Marematlou Freedom Party have filed an urgent application on the
Lesotho High Court to have the polls postponed because they want
the IEC to investigate alleged irregularities.
</P>
<P>
One of the alleged irregularities was that about 80 percent of
voters in one village were reportedly born on a New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the parties' complaint that the IEC did not give
them sufficient time to examine the voters' list, the IEC
chairman said it was ironic because the same parties had rejected
the IEC's previously proposed poll date of August this year.
</P>
<P>
"They rejected our proposal... stressing they wanted the
elections... We had to give a short period of six days to inspect
the provisional list made public on April 14," Mafisa said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was sad that the leaders took the court action
knowing that the IEC is operating "on a tight time table".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy, which
was formed after breaking away from the Basotholand Congress
Party last year, on Sunday also criticized the opposition's court
move.
</P>
<P>
More than one hundred international observers have arrived in
the country and election materials have been sent out to various
voting stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
