<HEADLINE> Russian Envoy Briefs Egyptian Official on Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Middle East Envoy Viktor
Posuvalyuk Sunday briefed Egyptian officials on the results of his
recent visits to a number of Mideast countries, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting between Egyptian Assistant Foreign Minister
Ahmed Abu el-Gheit, and Posuvalyuk, also Russian deputy foreign
minister, the two evaluated the current situation in the Middle
East and the U.S. efforts to activate the peace process on the
Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
The Russian diplomat has paid visits to Palestinian self-rule
Gaza area, Syria and Lebanon and held talks with Palestinian,
Syrian and Lebanese officials on how to revive the Arab talks with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The two officials also examined Israel's conditional
application of U.N. Resolution 425 on withdrawal from south
Lebanon and Russia's contacts with U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In April, Israel decided to endorse the resolution but
conditioned its withdrawal from south Lebanon on Beirut's security
guarantees for the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk also conveyed to el-Gheit a verbal message from
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov to his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa on preparation for a visit by Russian
President Boris Yeltsin to Egypt early next year.
</P>
<P>
Russia was the co-sponsor of the Mideast peace process together
with the U.S. at the 1991 Madrid peace conference. 
</P>
