<HEADLINE> Euro-Med Partnership Affected by Stalled Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said on Sunday the latest
developments in the Mideast peace process have negatively affected
the Euro-Mediterranean partnership, or Barcelona process.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona process is affected by the Mideast peace process
as many of its participants are also involved in the peace march,
Egyptian Assistant Foreign Minister for European Affairs Fathi
Al-Shazli said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shazli made the remarks before leaving for Brussels,
Belgium, to attend meetings due on Monday of senior officials of
the Barcelona process participants.
</P>
<P>
He described the Euro-Med partnership as a "comprehensive
strategic style."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian official voiced hope that the Barcelona process
would be accelerated so that it would help promote the Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Euro-Med partnership is aimed at developing security,
political, economic, cultural and social ties between the 15
European Union members and 12 countries along the southern
Mediterranean basin.
</P>
<P>
The first partnership conference was held in Barcelona, Spain,
in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
It includes eight Arab countries, namely Algeria, Egypt,
Jordan, Lebanon, Morocco, the Palestinian National Authority,
Syria and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the aforesaid Arab countries will hold
a meeting in Beirut to coordinate stances before foreign ministers
of the Barcelona process states meet in Palermo, Italy, on June
3-4 to review the resolutions adopted at the Barcelona meeting.
</P>
<P>
Morocco, Tunisia, Jordan and the Palestinian National Authority
have signed partnership agreements with EU's Mediterranean
countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Syria, Lebanon and Algeria are expected to be among the
countries which will conclude similar agreements with the EU in
the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
