<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-17 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni council of ministers has approved a project
to modernize the oil refineries in Aden and Maareb through the
participation of new investors who can manage, operate and market
the products both locally and internationally.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Abdul Qader
Ba-jammal said Saturday that the Yemeni government will hold no
more than 30 percent of the refineries' shares.
</P>
<P>
The modernization program will approximately cost 360 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran has announced to lower its "economic ties" with
Buenos Aires, after Argentina recalled all diplomats here except
the charge d'affaires, and reduced diplomatic relations "to the
minimum."
</P>
<P>
Tehran radio on Sunday quoted Foreign Ministry spokesman
Mahmoud Mohammadi as saying that Iran made the decision following
the repeated "baseless accusations" that Iran were behind two
blasts in Buenos Aires in 1992 and 1994 which killed 114 people.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman failed to mention what measures will be
actually taken to effect the reduction of "economic ties."
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran has invited international bidding for the
project of building a pipeline to transfer oil from the Caspian
Sea to the Persian Gulf, local daily Iran News reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The National Iranian Oil Company (NIOC) said the 392-kilometer
pipeline, linking Neka in the northern province of Mazadaran, and
Rey near the capital Tehran, will be built through exchange
programs with Iranian oil.
</P>
<P>
The NIOC estimated the project would cost 300 to 400 million
U.S. dollars in a period of two years, hoping the construction
would begin by the end of the current Iranian calendar year (March
21, 1999).
</P>
<P>
The pipeline is to have a daily transferring capacity of
380,000 barrels, and probably make Iran the quickest and cheapest
route for shipping oil from the Caspian Sea region to the outside
world, earlier reports said.
</P>
<P>
Iran announced the construction of this pipeline after some
Caspian littoral states decided to lay a pipeline on the Caspian
seabed between Turkmenistan and Azerbaijan Republic, a move
rejected by Iran on the ground that it might pose a serious threat
to the sea's environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
