<HEADLINE> Namibian President Calls for Debt Relief for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam Nujoma
Sunday called for debt relief for developing countries,
especially for Africa.
</P>
<P>
Opening the 1998 Southern African Economic Forum in capital
Windhoek, Nujoma said the developing countries's economic
activities were constrained by heavy debt burdens, South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"What I am advocating here is for the debt of the developing
countries to be written off in order to allow them to spend their
resources on industrial change, human resource development and
productive economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is where we can move away from debt serving and
development aid and concentrate on trade and economic
prosperity," he said to warm applause from the about 850
delegates from 60 countries who were attending the summit.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma expressed disappointment at the low level of foreign
investment in the region, which had been almost exclusively in
resource-based activities.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned that Africa's natural resources are
exploited and exported in raw form and the prices of these
commodities have remained low," he said, adding that goods
produced were then imported at a very high prices.
</P>
<P>
He said his country is looking for a balance in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on the day, Zambian President Chiluba appealed to
northern hemisphere countries and international organizations to
eliminate African states' debts as a recognition of the
countries' efforts in introducing economic and political reforms.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who is attending the economic summit, said countries
of the north could not "say they were helping Africa to reform
while they were holding a gun to its head."
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting was jointly organized by the World
Economic Forum and the 14-nation Southern African Development
Community (SADC) trading bloc.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe, Democratic Republic of Congo President
Laurent Kabila and Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano attended
the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
