<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Architectural Exhibition Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition sharing the
experience of local and French architects in building modern city
projects was opened Monday at the Hong Kong Science Museum's
Special Exhibition Hall.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, which is jointly presented by the Provisional
Urban Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and
the Consulate General of France in Hong Kong, will be open to the
public starting Tuesday until June 21 as one of the highlights of
Le French May Festival.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "From the Building to the City: France and Hong Kong
Experiences", the exhibition features examples of architectural
projects including Hong Kong's new airport at Chek Lap Kok, the
new World Cup stadium in Paris (the Stade de France), and four
other outstanding French architectural projects built in different
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
These include the Shanghai Pudong International Airport, the
Shanghai Opera House, the Nam Seoul Station for high speed train
in South Korea, and a new town in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
On display are seven models of the projects and a large number
of photographs, plans, drawings and videos to illustrate how
aesthetically appealing and technical infrastructures in urban
city are designed.
</P>
<P>
The New Hong Kong International Airport is the highlight of the
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the biggest infrastructure projects in the world
and is made up of 10 core projects comprising an airport with
world-class facilities, six railway and highway projects, two
reclamation projects and a new town.
</P>
<P>
The Stade de France is the new stadium built to hold the
spectacular 1998 Football World Cup.
</P>
<P>
This disc-shaped structure is an award winner in the
international architectural design competition Le Grand Stade de
France in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Pudong International Airport, which is scheduled
for completion in 1999, has been built following the basic
principle of flexibility to allow for future expansion needs.
</P>
<P>
The design concept of the Shanghai Opera House is the winning
proposal in an international architectural competition among 18
teams representing six countries including Canada, Japan,
Australia, United States, China and France.
</P>
<P>
The structure is under construction in the People's Square in
the center of the city of Shanghai, the biggest city in China.
</P>
<P>
The Nam Seoul station project is one of the six new stations
established along the new Seoul to Pusan line High Speed Train.
</P>
<P>
This new station demonstrates how it can play a role in
connecting instead of separating a city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
