<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Uninsured Children Eligible for Medicaid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A government study finds
previous assessments greatly underestimated the number of
uninsured children who qualify for Medicaid in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The new count of 4.7 million children -- up from the nearly 3
million previously calculated -- comes as states begin to enroll
children in a new health insurance program designed to cover those
missed by Medicaid -- the federal insurance program covering
millions of poor, elderly and disabled Americans, including those
on welfare, low-income children and pregnant women, and the
elderly poor who need institutional care.
</P>
<P>
The earlier estimates did not account for children who became
eligible for the program because of states' efforts to expand
eligibility beyond the federal minimums, said a co-author of the
study, which was being released Monday.
</P>
<P>
With about 10 million uninsured children, Congress and
President Bill Clinton agreed last year to a new program for
children who are not poor enough for Medicaid but whose families
cannot afford to buy insurance on their own.
</P>
<P>
The program is attractive to states because the federal
government pays a larger percentage of the cost of insurance than
it does under Medicaid, which is also funded by a combination of
federal and state money.
</P>
<P>
The higher number of potential Medicaid children may have
financial implications for states who aggressively recruit
children into the new program. If states find children who are
Medicaid-eligible, they must enroll them into Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
Even before the higher estimates surfaced, the Clinton
administration was concerned that so many eligible children have
not enrolled in Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
The administration is also encouraging states to make it easier
for children to sign up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Forest Fire Still Raging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A serious forest fire which broke
out in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region on May 13
had still not been brought under control today.
</P>
<P>
About 4,500 people, including forest farm staff, have been
mobilized, as well as five planes and 100 vehicles, to fight the
blaze, which had destroyed 13,000 ha of forest land by this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The blaze broke out at a forest farm in Xing'an League
(county), in the middle part of the Greater Xing'an Range, and
rapidly spread to neighboring Hulun Buir League on May 15, to the
northwest of the range.
</P>
<P>
A local official said that the cause of the fire was lightning
strikes as a result of high temperatures and strong winds during a
two-week drought in early May.
</P>
<P>
The fire is difficult to put out because the terrain makes
access to the blaze area difficult, and the thick leaf layer on
the ground enables the flames to travel swiftly, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Moderate to strong breezes with drizzle started tonight over
the affected area and are expected to continue into tomorrow,
bringing conditions favorable for controlling the fire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local governments will try to induce artificial rain
tonight in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
