<HEADLINE> Arafat, Albright Hold Talks in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright held a surprise
talk here Monday to discuss the stalled Middle East peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Albright telephoned Arafat, who was in Oslo to attend a
Socialist International meeting, in the middle of the night to
invite him for the surprise talks in London.
</P>
<P>
Albright has been trying to broker an interim deal under which
Israel would hand over a further 13 percent of the occupied West
Bank in return for extra Palestinian security measures.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have already accepted the U.S. proposals but
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has so far refused to
give up that much land.
</P>
<P>
Before flying into London, Arafat told reporters in Oslo, "I
hope she has achieved something with Netanyahu."
</P>
<P>
Albright met Netanyahu twice last week in Washington without
achieving a breakthrough, and U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross
had a further meeting with the Israeli leader Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Some progress was reported to have been made at Sunday's
meeting, aimed at breaking the deadlocked Arab-Israeli peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Arafat said the Palestinian president could
hold a meeting with British Prime Minister Tony Blair after the
talks with Albright. 
</P>
</TEXT>
