<HEADLINE> China Establishes Training Center for Light Aircraft Pilots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- China's first school for training
pilots and ground crew for light aircraft was established today at
the Beijing University of Aeronautics and Astronautics.
</P>
<P>
Approved by the Civil Aviation Administration of China, the
experiment and training center will enroll Chinese students from
the age of 17 and having finished senior high school. Pilots who
do not yet have licenses and foreign students are also eligible to
study there.
</P>
<P>
Students will be trained for one or two months; then they may
apply for flying licenses after passing a test and a physical
examination.
</P>
<P>
Light aircraft, mainly used for recreation, are popular in
developed countries because they are simple in structure, easy to
operate and have few requirements for taking off and landing.
</P>
<P>
China's light aircraft are at present used mainly for crop
spraying, photography and sightseeing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
