<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Seminer on Gender Opens in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A three-day international meeting
on gender and good governance started in Harare Monday to map out
strategies to increase the number of women in politics.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony Monday, Zimbabwe's National Affairs,
Employment Creation and Cooperatives Minister Thenjiwe Lesabe
said the participation of women in politics and decision-making
was essential to achieve transparency in governance.
</P>
<P>
She said the few who manage to reach top echelons often found
it difficult to make any impact on decisions which were being
made.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was organized by women in development division of
the Netherlands Ministry of Foreign Affairs in collaboration with
the royal Netherlands embassy here.
</P>
<P>
It will provide a forum for women and men who are involved in
politics, decision-making in government and policy-making or in
empowering women in the political arena.
</P>
<P>
Netherlands Ambassador to Zimbabwe Wim Wessels told the
meeting that the Beijing conference on women held in 1995 had
increased the international commitment to the eradication of
inequalities between women and men.
</P>
<P>
''More equitable relations without exploitation, violence and the
denial of human rights should be pursued,'' Wessels said.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Africa, Asia and Latin America are attending
the meeting to discuss the role of women in good governance and
democratic processes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
