<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Diplomats Evacuated from Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Non-essential staff at the
South African embassy in Jakarta, Indonesia, have been evacuated
following massive rioting in the country's capital, the Foreign
Affairs Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The evacuated people are on their way home, the department
said.
</P>
<P>
There were wide-spread riots and looting in Indonesia's
capital city of Jakarta over the past few days, during which
hundreds of people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said hundreds of shops and buildings were
also destroyed during the rioting.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors had postponed their investment plans in the
country as a result of the riots.
</P>
<P>
South African spokesman Linford Andrews was quoted as saying
that while Jakarta appeared to be calm, high-ranking South
African diplomats had been moved to a hotel as a security
precaution.
</P>
<P>
Andrews said the embassy would be closed for most of the week.
The situation was being monitored closely and a decision would be
taken on Friday whether to reopen the embassy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
