<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG Vows to "Seek Common Ground" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Portuguese chief
representatives of the Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group (JLG)
have agreed to seek common ground while reserving differences in
the final stage of Macao's transition.
</P>
<P>
Han Zhaokang, chief representative of the Chinese side, and his
Portuguese counterpart, Antonio Carlos, agreed at a meeting here
on Monday that the best and most effective way to handle the work
of the JLG in the remaining days before the handover is to "seek
common ground while reserving differences."
</P>
<P>
Han told reporters after a four-hour closed-door meeting that
the two sides exchanged ideas on four major topics of concern
during the meeting. They include:
</P>
<P>
-- the participation of the Chinese side in the preparation of
the budget for 1999 and for the year 2000 in Macao;
</P>
<P>
-- the pension system of retired civil servants in Macao;
</P>
<P>
-- the conditions for the transition to the future Macao
Special Administrative Region (SAR) of foreign advisors and
technicians currently hired by the Macao Government;
</P>
<P>
-- the formulation of detailed regulations on the
implementation of both official languages -- Chinese and
Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
"Due to the importance and complexity of the issues, we have
different views on them. But we have exchanged ideas in a
practical way and that helped us know each other's stand better,"
Han said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that China is sincere and determined to carry out
the policy of "one country, two systems" and "Macao people
administering Macao under a high degree of autonomy."
</P>
<P>
Carlos said he agreed with Han, adding that "we will work in
accordance with the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration and the
instructions of our (Portuguese) political leaders."
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to hold further talks on those issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
