<HEADLINE> Indonesian Armed Forces Back Peaceful Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI)
have said that they back an orderly and peaceful implementation of
reforms in the country, official Antara News Agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
ABRI are keen to carrying out reforms, Lt. Gen. S. Bambang
Yudhoyono, chief for sociopolitical affairs, said here late
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"As what the defense minister and ABRI commander (Gen. Wiranto)
has said, ABRI are seriously preparing a comprehensive concept on
political, economic and legal reforms," Yudhoyono said.
</P>
<P>
However, he reminded that the needed reforms should be "from
the people, by the people and for the people" and that they
require not only "structural but also cultural steps."
</P>
<P>
The reforms, he said, as student activists across the country
have been demanding in the past three months, should also have a
clear agenda.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that unity should be maintained because it will
serve as a vehicle that will haul the country out of its economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
ABRI welcome constructive ideas on the necessary reforms, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
