<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Cooperate With China on Hydro Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister for Water Resources Shailaja Acharya said here Monday
that her country supports China's initiative for setting up a
joint-venture corporation to tap Nepal's huge water resources.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with a Chinese business delegation, Miss Acharya
said that electric power is needed for Nepal's economic
development. Now Nepal prefers small-and-medium-sized hydro-power
stations to large ones, because the former produce an instant
effect while the latter are more costly and cause disputes among
the political parties.
</P>
<P>
She said that her country will extend its full cooperation to
the Chinese side in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Yan Keqiang, vice chairman of All China Federation of Industry
and Commerce and vice minister for water conservancy of China,
said that non-governmental cooperation between China and Nepal has
been strengthened after the Nepal-China Non-governmental
Cooperation Forum was established in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said his delegation comprises private entrepreneurs and
experts on hydro power, and he hopes that his visit is fruitful in
the two aspects.
</P>
<P>
He said that the development of Nepal's water resources is good
for the country's economic development, so there is a great
potential for Sino-Nepalese cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The 14-member Chinese delegation arrived in Kathmandu on Monday
for a six-day visit, which aims to explore the possibility of
joint-venture projects in Nepal especially in the field of hydro
power, and further strengthen trade and economic cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Yan Keqiang also called on Nepali Finance Minister
Ram Saran Mahat and Minister for Industry and Labor Dhundi Raj
Shastri. They both expressed their support for a joint-venture
corporation in Nepal for the construction of
small-and-medium-sized hydro-power stations in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese entrepreneurs discussed with their
Nepalese counterparts the possibility of setting up joint-ventures
in Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
