<HEADLINE> Blair Says Deal Reached on U.S. Trade Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 18 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Monday that the European Union (EU) had reached an
agreement with the United States to waive U.S. sanctions on EU,
Russian and Malaysian firms.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference after a EU-U.S. summit meeting in Downing
Street, Blair said: "What we have established today is at least a
basis for a lasting solution to these problems."
</P>
<P>
Three companies, one from each country, are involved in a
disputed 2 billion U.S. dollar gas deal with Iran. The companies
are Total of France, Russia's Gazprom, and Petronas of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Blair hailed the deal as "a real step forward" though there is
still more work to do.
</P>
<P>
"We have avoided a showdown over sanctions, with which we don't
agree, and we have done it in a way that at least provides the
chance of a solution to the problem in the future."
</P>
<P>
Blair said the deal would cement EU-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, the leaders also launched a new bilateral trade
initiative called the "Transatlantic Economic Partnership." They
have also agreed to work to promote multilateral trade
liberalization and dismantle trade barriers on both sides of the
Atlantic Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
