<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Relief Debated in Southern African Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The issue of whether
impoverished African states' debts should be forgiven is the
subject of a heated debate at the ongoing southern African
economic summit in Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma, Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba and Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano Sunday called
on the west to cancel debts in those countries which had
undertaken political and economic reform.
</P>
<P>
However, economists attending the conference said Monday that
governments would have to give something in exchange for debt
forgiveness, such as commitment to structured recovery plans,
South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Nico Czypionka, group economist for Standard Bank, a major
bank operating in a number of southern African countries, said it
did not look good when African leaders called for debt relief and
arrived at the conference in Falcon 5000 jets.
</P>
<P>
He warned about the dangers of creating a populist
ground-swell against debt repayment, saying the financial markets
would punish those countries seen as unlikely to pay back loans.
</P>
<P>
Chief economist for another leading bank, Rand Merchant Bank,
echoed his view, saying conditionalities should be attached to
debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit, aimed at promoting economic cooperation
in southern Africa and building bridges between the region and
the rest of the world, was opened Sunday in Windhoek. It drew
senior government officials and business leaders from 60
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
