<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Parliament Leader Praises Chinese Muslims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Wan Muhamad Noor Matha, speaker of
the National Assembly of Thailand, heading a 23-member
parliamentary delegation, paid a two-day visit from May 16 to 17
to the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in northwest China which has
some 1.7 million people of the Hui (Moslem) nationality, or one
third of the region's population.
</P>
<P>
In Daxin, a suburban town of the regional capital Yinchuan, Wan
walked into one of the farm houses built in distinct Islamic
architectural style, and was invited to taste Hui snacks and had a
good chat with the house owner, Yang Yongshan.
</P>
<P>
Yang's family earns over 30,000 yuan (about 3,750 US dollars) a
year by growing grain and vegetables, and Yang has sent his
daughter to study at a university.
</P>
<P>
It's just amazing, said Wan, also the speaker of the Thai House
of Representatives. Though Ningxia is classified as one of the
less-developed regions in China, people here are living far better
lives than we thought, he said.
</P>
<P>
He was especially attracted by the Xiguan Grand Mosque in
Yinchuan. The mosque has a history of over 300 years and is the
main place for Moslems in the city to carry out religious
activities.
</P>
<P>
Xie Shengling, director of the region's Islamic Association,
told the Thai parliament leader that there are over 2,700 mosques
in the autonomous region, which are managed by about 1,600
imams. So far, more than 1,700 Huis in the region have made
pilgrimages to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
Wan also visited the Second Northwest Nationalities Institute
to learn about the funding of the institute of higher learning for
ethnic minorities, the employment prospects for the students and
how it helps to protect the languages of ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
He said he was impressed by what the Chinese government has
done for people of ethnic minorities, its educational policies in
these regions in particular.
</P>
<P>
From what he saw in ningxia, the Chinese government's policies
toward ethnic minorities and religious beliefs have achieved great
success, he remarked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
