<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruggiero Calls on WTO Members to Resist Protectionism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) should resist protectionist pressures following
the Asian financial crisis, said WTO Director-General Renato
Ruggiero here Monday.
</P>
<P>
It would be "wrong to underestimate the effects of the Asian
financial crisis," Ruggiero told trade ministers at the opening
session of the second WTO ministerial conference.
</P>
<P>
"The repercussions on current accounts are just beginning to be
felt, which means that protectionist pressures could become much
stronger," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the ministers to send "a strong signal" to demonstrate
their resistance to the pressure, and to emphasize the point that
keeping trade open is the road to renewed growth.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the industrialized members to do more to help
the poor, and to overcome an "unacceptable level of poverty and
inequality" in the world.
</P>
<P>
WTO is holding a three-day conference here in Geneva on May
18-20.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton, expected to address the conference
this evening, will make an argument similar to Ruggiero's that
open trade is vital for prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
