<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Leaves for France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak left
here Monday for France on a three-day visit aimed at drumming up
European support for the Middle East peace process and expanding
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Mubarak and French President Jacques Chirac
will issue a "special statement" on the Mideast peace process,
Egypt's official Middle East News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The statement would outline the two leaders' visualization of
the immediate steps to be taken to spare the region a whirlpool of
violence and get out of the 15-month impasse in the peace talks
between the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents are expected to brief each other on last
week's Group-15 summit of developing nations held in Cairo and the
summit of Group-8 in Britain attended by seven most developed
western countries, including France, and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say France' historical ties with many countries in the
Middle East make it an ideal advocate of Arab political and
economic interests in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Apart from international and regional affairs, Mubarak is to
exert efforts to promote bilateral trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Public Business Sector Atef Mohamed Ebeid
has said that more than 120 businessmen travelling with Mubarak
are expected to boost Egypt's exports, offer at least 15 projects
to French investors and reach deals on technology transfer.
</P>
<P>
France is Egypt's fourth largest trading partner. In 1997,
bilateral trade volume stood at 1.4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
