<HEADLINE> Pak FM, Japanese Envoy Hold Talks on Indian Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan Monday held talks with Japanese special envoy Seiichiro
Noboru on the situation arisen out of Indian nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Gohar briefed Noboru on the Indian hostility towards Pakistan
and the serious threat posed to its security by the Indian nuclear
tests, according to a press release issued here by the Foreign
Office Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister deeply regretted that the Group-8
countries were totally in sensitive to this situation.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan will take all aspects into account before
taking any final decision which will be in keeping with the
magnitude of the threat faced by Pakistan and in consonance with
the requirements of Pakistan's security and national interest.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese envoy spoke of the country's sanctions imposed on
India against its nuclear tests and nuclear weaponization.
</P>
<P>
Noboru said that as a result of the extremely regrettable
Indian action the Japanese people had felt a sense of outrage.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, in a brief press talk after the 45-minute
meeting with the Pakistani foreign minister, Noboru said that
Japan hopes Pakistan to be "exercise utmost restraint" in its
response to the Indian nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Japanese leaders have indicated that it would impose sanctions
against Pakistan when it follows India's lead and conducts nuclear
tests. Japan is providing aid worth 500 million dollars a year to
Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
