<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Registers as Voter for Congress Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Second Prime Minister
and Vice President of the Cambodian People's Party (CPP) Hun Sen has
registered as a voter for the upcoming congress elections.
</P>
<P>
He and his wife registered Monday afternoon at the Teacher
Training College in Kandal province, which is not far from his
home and often referred to as the ``Tiger's Lair.''
</P>
<P>
It was the first day for voters to register for Assembly
elections on July 26. Voter registration will last for 28 days
until June 15.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian people need the elections and the international
community also hopes to see the elections take place, Hun Sen said
to reporters after registering.
</P>
<P>
He said the congressional elections would take place as
scheduled and that attempts to postpone the elections would be
doomed to failure, referring to a request for postponement by the
National United Front (NUF).
</P>
<P>
The NUF, which consists of the Funcinpec, the Sam Rainsy Party,
the Son Sann Party and the Cambodian Neutral Party, said in a
joint statement on Monday that the elections, if conducted under
present conditions, would be illegal and unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
They are demanding that the elections be postponed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition Sam Rainsy Party has charged that
registration officials have allowed only those people accompanied
by CPP unit leaders to register.
</P>
<P>
This suggests that only those who have promised to vote for the
CPP are being allowed to register, the Sam Rainsy Party said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
It is urging all observers, Cambodian and international, not to
turn a blind eye to these gross abuses of voter rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
