<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Not Ready to Consider Legal Action Against Microsoft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC) said
it's not ready to take action against Microsoft after the software
company and the U.S. government failed in their negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Stefan Rating, spokesman for European Competition Commissioner
Karel van Miert, told the press that the commission has not yet
begun to deliberate on whether or not to take action against the
software giant as it has done before in other anti-trust cases.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations between U.S. government lawyers and Microsoft
collapsed without any sign of resuming. The government and at
least 20 U.S. states will soon file two separate but similar
federal anti-trust lawsuits against Microsoft in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The EC spokesman said the commission would prefer to wait for
the Americans to implement action.
</P>
<P>
When pressed by a question that it might take the Americans
years to take action, the spokesman said that it may just as well
take years for the commission to take action.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft's new Windows version was accused of breaching
U.S. anti-trust laws by illegally using its market power to
suffocate competition in the market for Internet browser
software.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft has included its own browser for free in its Windows
98 to be shipped on June 25.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, previously launched an investigation into allegations that
Microsoft allegedly breached anti-trust laws with its earlier
version of the Windows software. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
