<HEADLINE> ``Non-Communists Need to Contribute to Re-Employment Efforts'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- China's non-Communist personages
should contribute actively to helping the work of guaranteeing the
basic livelihood and re-employment of laid-off workers, said Wang
Zhaoguo, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), here today.
</P>
<P>
The remark came when he gave a briefing on the guidelines for a
work conference on re-employment to the leaders of China's
non-communist parties and the All-China Federation of Industry and
Commerce (ACFIC), as well as some personages without party
affiliation.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who is also head of the United Front Work Department of
the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), said
that guaranteeing the basic livelihood and re-employment of
laid-off workers is an important way for the non-communist parties
and the ACFIC to participate in political and government affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped the non-Communist personages would give full
play to their role in contacting people of all walks of life and
helping laid-off workers form a new concept of employment in line
with the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The ACFIC, as a non-governmental business organization linking
China's non-state-owned economic sectors, should organize and
direct more non-state-owned enterprises to participate in this
work, and encourage them to recruit laid-off workers and their
children, he said.
</P>
<P>
Big privately-run enterprises should be encouraged to
participate in the reform of the state-owned enterprises by such
means as merger and purchase in order to reduce the number of
layoffs and ease the pressure for employment, Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
