<HEADLINE> Trade Disputes Top EU-US Summit Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 18 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
United States President Bill Clinton, and European Union
Commission President Jacques Santer launched discussions over
EU-US trade disputes on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Officials predicted the meeting would lead to "some
progress both on ILSA and Helms-Burton."
</P>
<P>
ILSA, known as the D'Amato Law, allows Washington to penalize
foreign companies investing more than 40 million U.S. dollars per
year in the hydrocarbon sector in Iran or Libya.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton Law penalizes foreign businesses which engage
in business with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The EU has strongly opposed the U.S. laws, saying
"extraterritorial" laws that seek to bind other countries break
international law.
</P>
<P>
Just hours ahead of the summit, EU External Trade Commissioner,
Leon Brittan, said progress had been made in talks to end the row
and a deal is in sight.
</P>
<P>
"We haven't got it in the bag, but we've made huge progress. We
have been negotiating intensively over the weekend, and I very
much hope we can now bring it to a conclusion," he told BBC.
</P>
</TEXT>
