<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Current Account Surplus Posts New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union current account
surplus, including intra-EU transactions, soared to a new record
high of 83.5 billion ECU in 1996, Eurostat reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus was 134 percent up on the previous high of 35.6
billion ECU registered in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Trade in goods, according to the EU statistical office,
contributed a 60 percent share of the current increase in the
account with the surplus rising by 25 percent to stand at 129.1
billion ECU.
</P>
<P>
Surplus on trade in services grew 184 percent to reach 6.2
billion ECU representing 17 percent of total EU transactions.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union, however, was still trading primarily with
itself, the Luxembourg-based statistical office claimed, with the
United States and Japan being the major trading partners outside
the union.
</P>
<P>
The current account surplus with the United States was reduced
by 44 percent to 3.8 billion ECU in 1996, while surplus on trade
in services rose with Japan, from 4.9 billion ECU in 1995 to 6.9
billion ECU in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
