<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Urged to Press Ahead with Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa would have to
press ahead with economic reforms despite the fact that they may
cause short-term hardship, Botswanan President Festus Mogae said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing businessmen on the second day of the southern
African economic summit in Windhoek, Namibia, Mogae said Botswana
was trying to diversify its economy away from mining and
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"We are worried about our excessive dependence on those," said
Mogae, the former finance minister and one of the architects of
Botswana's present economic policy.
</P>
<P>
Attracting foreign investment was a priority and one way of
doing this was to deregulate further, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the process had to take time but there were
constraints, including trying to persuade labor that policies
which would result in jobs in two years' time "were not pie in
the sky", Mogae said.
</P>
<P>
Botswana had the world's fastest-growing economy between 1965
and 1996, the World Bank's latest figures showed. The country's
gross national product (GNP) grew by 13 percent over the 31-year
period and its income per capita grew by 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on regional trade cooperation, Mogae suggested that
South Africa was not doing enough to ensure free movement of
goods within the Southern African Customs Union (SACU), which
also groups Lesotho, Botswana, Namibia and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
He said he sometimes had the feeling that South Africa and
Zimbabwe introduced non-tariff barriers against Botswanan goods.
He said Botswana's ability to reduce tariff barriers was
dependent on the SACU.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit was jointly organized by the 14-nation
South African Community (SADC) trading bloc and the World
Economic Forum, a Geneva-based organization whose members include
1,000 of the world's largest companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Luxembourg Sign Securities Market Supervision Memorandum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- China and Luxembourg signed a
memorandum of understanding on cooperation in supervision of the
securities and futures market here today.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum marks a new stage in securities and futures
cooperation between China and Luxembourg, and opens a new channel
for the two countries to exchange personnel and information on
securities and futures market supervision, both parties agreed.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Zhengqing, chairman of the China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC), said at the signing ceremony that China's
securities market has entered a development period of
standardization and become part of the country's market economy
system.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis has highlighted the great importance
of international cooperation in securities and futures for the
prevention of financial risks, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Charles Kietter, commissioner of the Luxembourg Stock Exchange
Supervisory Authority, said that Luxembourg is willing to assist
Chinese enterprises in their efforts to be listed and raise funds
in Luxembourg, and to provide China with technical assistance in
connection with securities and futures market supervision, thereby
contributing to the development of China's securities market.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg has a highly internationalized securities and
futures market. It has 1,400 investment funds, with assets
totalling 420 billion US dollars, the fourth-largest amount of
such assets in the world.
</P>
<P>
Currently, a dozen bonds, including ones issued by the Chinese
government, the Bank of China and the China Investment Bank, are
listed in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The CSRC has already signed memorandums of understanding on
cooperation in supervision of the securities and futures market
with 10 other countries and the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
