<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Issue Tenders for Tilt Trains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel is going to issue tenders
soon for the purchase of rail systems using the new "tilt"
technology, Israel Radio reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Israeli National Infrastructure Minister
Arie Sharon has ordered the Israel Railway Authority to prepare
the tenders.
</P>
<P>
The "tilt" technology enables trains to take curves at higher
speeds, and is therefore expected to encourage passenger traffic
on winding routes such as the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem line, a route
which, currently, is largely shunned by commuters because it is
so slow.
</P>
<P>
Sharon's decision follows the recent successful experiment with
the new system on the railways of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The tenders will be for the immediate purchase of seven
systems, at a cost of 25 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the new systems will constitute a
revolution in Israel's public transportation industry. They will
help bring the peripheral areas closer to the center of the
country, and will thereby promote employment and economic growth
in these areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
