<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Cooperation Expands Between China, Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- China sees infrastructural
construction, technical renovation of state-owned enterprises, and
cooperation between small and medium-size enterprises of China and
those of other countries as the key areas for foreign investment
in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Sheng Huaren, minister in charge of the State Economic and
Trade Commission, made the remarks during a meeting with Canadian
Industry Ministry John Manley here today.
</P>
<P>
China will introduce more foreign investments in those areas, he
said.
</P>
<P>
China is confident of meeting its goal of an 8-percent economic
growth rate this year, said Sheng, who became head of the
commission in a government restructuring in March.
</P>
<P>
He said the major areas for investment are energy,
transportation, environmental protection and water conservancy
projects.
</P>
<P>
He said the technical renovation in China's industrial sector
"provides a great deal of opportunities for overseas investors."
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises in China will adjust production mix,
reduce use of energy and materials, and improve efficiency
through extensive technical renovation in the next few years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises, which were "large in number and
extensive in field," could recruit a great amount of laborers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the state enterprises became a key area for
investment because they needed to enhance cooperation with
foreign partners to become more competitive in the global market.
</P>
<P>
Manley said Canada was interested in the Sino-Canadian
cooperation in small and medium-sized enterprises as well as in
water power industry and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation could be carried out on a more extensive scale,
he said, such as in the framework of Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Canada is ready to invest in the key projects in central China,
he added.
</P>
<P>
During his China tour, the Canadian minister will visit the
construction site of the Three Gorges Dam in central China with a
delegation of Canadian companies before going to China's densely
populated city of Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Canada plans to open its fourth consulate in this new
municipality, he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Sheng and Manley agreed to sign a bilateral memorandum of
understanding on economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade departments are consulting on signing the
agreement for the protection of mutual investment.
</P>
<P>
High-level visits between the two countries are frequent this
year. Canadian ministers of international trade and international
cooperation have visited China since March.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics by the Chinese Customs, the bilateral
trade volume reached 3.91 billion U.S. dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
