<HEADLINE> PNA to Reject Israeli Redeployment Plan: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
said Monday that Palestinians will reject a reported Israeli
proposal to carry out a 13 percent redeployment in the West Bank
without a third phase withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Shaath, Palestinian National Authority (PNA) planning and
international cooperation minister, said that the PNA will insist
on a third phrase withdrawal. The present U.S. proposal for a 13.1
percent withdrawal has already been "a huge compromise" on the
Palestinian part, he added.
</P>
<P>
A report from the U.S. said that during talks in Washington
Sunday night, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu agreed to
a 13 percent pullback from the West Bank provided the Palestinian
side gives up the idea of a third phase redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The report said this came after Washington threatened to
withdraw from the whole peace process if Netanyahu rejected the 13
percent pullback in the second Israeli troop redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who
flied to London Monday to participate in the U.S.-European Union
summit, will meet PNA President Yasser Arafat there Monday
afternoon to brief him on the latest talks she and U.S. Middle
East peace envoy Dennis Ross held with Netanyahu in
Washington. Arafat will arrive in London from a visit to Norway.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, after his five-day visit to the U.S., would return
to Israel Monday afternoon. He had said in Washington that he was
prepared to "make any compromise" if it does not endanger
Israel's security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
