<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined sharply on
the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) lost 30.29 points to close at 1291.74 points,
breaking the psychological resistance mark of 1300 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stocks ended lower on concerns that
Singapore's economic growth would weaken further and the crisis in
Indonesia worsen.
</P>
<P>
Market observers were mostly awaiting the outcome of mass
nationwide demonstrations expected on Wednesday in Indonesia, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators are expected to urge President Soeharto to step
down, posing what the observers described as the gravest ever
threat to his decades-long rule, they added.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 102.76 million units, valued
at 223.78 million Singapore dollars (134.81 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded stock as it
registered a turnover of 6.5 million units. It was followed by ST
(Singapore Technologies) Engineering which had 6.39 million shares
traded. TAC 200 was next with 6.13 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 15 cents to finish at 9.55 Singapore
dollars. TAC 200 increased by 11 cents to end at 1.33 U.S.
dollars. Clipsal was up by five cents to close at 1.25 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Seaview was the biggest loser as it declined
by 80 cents to end at 4.2 Singapore dollars. SIA (Singapore
Airlines) fell by 50 cents to close at 7.5 Singapore dollars,
while SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) was down by 40 cents to
finish at 14.2 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
