<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Difficulties Force IBF to Cancel Tournaments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The financial crises in Southeast
Asia had forced the International Badminton Federation (IBF) to
erase some of the scheduled tournaments off the calendar, a
leading IBF official disclosed here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
IBF, badminton's world governing body, had a very difficult
year with regard to the financial situation in the region, said
Datuk Punch Gunalan from Malaysia, vice-president of the IBF and
chairman of the IBF's Open Committee.
</P>
<P>
The federation had to cancel such events as the Korea Open,
Thailand Open, Vietnam Open and the Russia Open. And the Chinese
Taipei Open had been postponed from November this year to January
1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
But many tournaments would still stand, he said. As one of
them, the Indonesia Open would not only be held in August as
scheduled but also the Indonesian Badminton Association would try
to make it a Four-Star event. Such grade of tournament requires a
total prize money of at least 120,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This year's Grand Prix Final will be held in February 1999, to
give way to the Asian Games set for Bangkok in December this year,
said Gunalan, who is also secretary-general of the Asian Badminton
Confederation.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the Grand Prix Final, the world's top 16 for
men's singles and top 12 for women's singles, will be decided
according to the year's final world rankings which could be
finalized after the year-ending tournament, the Hong Kong Open,
which had been set for November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Handphones Used During Driving Are Confiscated in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- For the first time in Singapore,
five motorists had their cellular phones confiscated by the
Traffic Police for making calls while driving on Monday, the first
day the new traffic measure went into effect.
</P>
<P>
As of 5 p.m. Monday, five motorists had their cellular phones
confiscated by the police for handphone-driving, Singapore
television said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to confiscation of the mobile phones, the offenders
will also chalk up nine demerit points and pay a composition fine
of 170 Singapore dollars, or a bit more than 100 U.S. dollars, for
each offense. The confiscated handphones will be given to the
courts for disposal, the television said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Traffic Police decided to implement the new
handphone confiscation rule effective this Monday, because more
people have been committing the offense of handphone-driving.
</P>
<P>
The Traffic Police statistics showed that in the first four
months of this year, the number of handphone-driving offenders who
were booked by the police rose to about 220 a month from about 180
a month last year.
</P>
<P>
Police said that confiscation had been considered since last
year, when a blitz in October caught 300 offenders. Since then,
the police had been warning motorists repeatedly over the media
that it would introduce additional measures should the problem of
handphone-driving persist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
