<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Has Highest Polio Cases in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has the highest polio cases
in Africa, with 942 cases reported in 1997, the World Health
Organization (WHO) has said.
</P>
<P>
WHO's representative in Nigeria, Evarist Njelesani, made the
disclosure at the weekend in Lagos, at the meeting of the Rotary
International Sub-Sahara Africa Regional Polio Plus Committee.
</P>
<P>
Njelesani said Nigeria was followed by the Democratic Republic
of Congo with 219 cases.
</P>
<P>
As the WHO has set the year 2,000 for total elimination of
polio in the world, the official pointed out that in Africa,
polio-free zones are emerging in the Southern and Eastern belt.
</P>
<P>
Njelesani said surveillance for Acute Flaccid Paralysis (AFP)
has been initiated in each country which has conducted National
Immunization Day (NIDS) with a network of 13 laboratories for
stool specimen investigation.
</P>
<P>
In Nigeria, he said, four rounds of NIDS had been conducted in
the last two years, increasing coverage from 46 percent in 1996
to 95 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The WHO has actively assisted the Nigerian government to set
up a surveillance system for AFP, with over 2,000 health
personnel trained at the federal, state and local council levels.
</P>
<P>
The result is an increase of the number of cases of AFP from
only three reported in 1997 to five in January, nine in February,
17 in March and 25 in April 1998, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
