<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vajpayee to Visit Nuclear Explosion Sites on May 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee will visit the site of five recent nuclear tests in
Pokhran Range of Rajasthan State on May 20, official sources said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
India held five nuclear tests within 48 hours in May 11 and 13
at Pokhran, inducing strong reactions and sanctions from the
international community. The thermonuclear (45 kiloton), fission
(15 kiloton), and the low yield (0.2 kiloton) nuclear devices were
detonated simultaneously on May 11 and two more sub-kiloton
nuclear devices (0.5 and 0.3 kiloton) were triggered on May 13.
</P>
<P>
After the five nuclear tests, India announced that it acquired
nuclear weapons capability.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said that the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)
is taking advantage of the nuclear tests for the party. "Partisan
euphoria is sought to be built around the country's new-found
nuclear weapons capability," the reports quoted former prime
minister Inder Kumar Gujral as saying Monday. Other political
parties have time and again warned the BJP against taking
advantage for itself. Some reports even said that with this
advantage the BJP might call snap elections to secure a majority
in Parliament to get rid of its present coalition troubles.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee, however, ruled out mid-term elections to Parliament
to tap the goodwill generated by the nuclear tests Monday. He said
that there was no question of BJP taking advantage of the national
achievement.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, after the nuclear tests, residents of
Khetolal village at Pokhran have started complaining of various
complications. Over a dozen people so far complained of excessive
bleeding from the nose, skin and eye irritation, vomiting and
loose motions. The villagers said this started immediately after
the twin explosions on May 13 and continued thereafter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Ministry to Vaccinate Kids against Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will vaccinate
all children under five against polio in the latter half of the
year, according to a statement issued by the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian Monday quoted the statement as saying that
Tanzania is implementing strategies toward complete interruption
of transmission of the virus causing poliomyelitis, popularly
known as infantile paralysis.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed over the weekend by the acting
Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Health, Dr. G. Upunda,
said the move has been in line with a World Health Assembly (WHA)
resolution aiming at eradicating poliomyelitis in the whole world
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the vaccination days for 1998 will be
August 1 and 2 and September 12 and 13.
</P>
<P>
"All children, aged 0-5 years, are eligible to the vaccination
rounds irrespective of their immunization status and whether or
not they were vaccinated during the previous national
immunization days," it said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania conducted polio mass vaccination in 1996 and 1997 to
interrupt the transmission of the virus, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Senator Warns of Indian Expansionist Designs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Senator Akram Zaki
Monday said New Delhi's nuclear tests are a "brazen expression of
its expansionist designs."
</P>
<P>
"The Western world should not perceive the Pokhran explosions
as a luxury to climb to nuclear power status -- they have unmasked
the real face of India which harbors expansionist designs like the
Nazi Germans of the 1930s," said Zaki in an interview with the
official Associated Press of Pakistan (APP).
</P>
<P>
Zaki, who is chairman of the Senate's Standing Committee on
Foreign Affairs, said Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's
announcement that India will use nuclear power when attacked is
"an unambiguous confirmation of New Delhi's designs."
</P>
<P>
With its elaborate missile program, the Indian blasts
constitute a grave security threat to the entire range of
countries from those in the Middle East to New Zealand, Zaki said.
</P>
<P>
"Any miscalculation on the part of the Western world will be a
repeat of the mistake that took place before World War II when
they failed to perceive Nazi Germans' expansionist designs," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He called for a change in the Western perception that India is
a peaceful country as propagated by New Delhi. "The illusion
should no longer be there -- the Indian designs of aggression are
clear and manifest."
</P>
<P>
In response to a question about the world reaction in the event
of a Pakistan nuclear test, he said Pakistan has become immune to
sanctions as it has been subjected to them discriminately and for
a long time.
</P>
<P>
Zaki is a member of the delegation that leaves for the United
States in a couple of days as part of Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif's diplomatic drive to apprise the international community
of Pakistan's security concerns in the wake of the Indian nuclear
blasts.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will meet top U.S. senators and congressmen to
underscore Pakistan's steps for its security as "a necessity of
survival."
</P>
<P>
In addition, the delegation will also mobilize the Pakistani
community in the United States to convey their country's
legitimate security concerns to the Clinton administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Hopes Pakistan to Be Restraint on Nuclear Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan Monday expressed the hope
that Pakistan would exercise "utmost restraint" in its response to
Indian nuclear tests last week.
</P>
<P>
After a 45-minute meeting with Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan Monday, Japanese special envoy Seiichiro Noboru told
reporters that "we hope that Pakistan would exercise utmost
restraint."
</P>
<P>
Noboru said in a brief press talk that the foreign minister did
not tell him if Pakistan has decided to explode a nuclear device
or not.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is carefully reviewing the situation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question what Pakistan will gain by not
carrying out a nuclear test, the Japanese envoy said, "the world
opinion is already very sympathetic with Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
To another question what Japan will do if Pakistan detonate a
nuclear device, he said, "you will know it very soon."
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Noboru, who arrived here Sunday, asked
Gohar to convey a message from Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto to Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Japanese leaders have indicated that it would impose sanctions
against Pakistan when it follows India's lead and conducts nuclear
tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
