<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria May Prune Varsities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The 23 federal universities across
Nigeria may be reduced to six in line with the country's
geo-political zones under a new policy on the future of
education, the Daily Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The six geo-political zones are Northeast, Northwest, North
Central, Southwest, Southeast and Southsouth, believed to be
divided for a balance of tribal interests.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policy, the funding and management of the six
universities would be the responsibility of the government, while
those left would be transferred to the 36 states all over the
country, the report said, quoting Education Minister Alhaji Dauda
Birmah.
</P>
<P>
The policy was fashioned by a seven-man inter-ministerial
committee headed by the minister.
</P>
<P>
According to the policy, the federal government would continue
to establish model secondary schools and maintain its own
tertiary institutions when the states are responsible for the
management of the remaining universities, polytechnics and
secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
The minister said primary education would henceforth be the
sole responsibility of local governments and private initiatives
in the geo-political zones with each zone at liberty to determine
the status of its primary education.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister at the weekend, the federal
government would in the next 45 days announce the establishment
of a National Commission for Secondary Education.
</P>
<P>
Also being considered was a proposal to decentralize the
present National Primary Education Commission into a six zonal
structure with each zone having its own commission.
</P>
<P>
Education in Nigeria has been reported in crisis, with absence
of mass education, lack of direction, inadequate expansion, poor
primary school foundation and commercialization of education
identified as major factors hintering the education sector.
</P>
<P>
The government has been urged to adopt an urgent realistic
policy to rescue the system from impending collapse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
