<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Currency Depreciation not to Affect Budget: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The recent sharp depreciation of
Uganda shilling against U.S. Dollar will not affect the country's
budget, a finance official has said.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said: "the
effect should be neutral. The value of imports in Dollars will go
up so that even if imports fall revenue will remain quite
stable."
</P>
<P>
"Our greatest concern is to ensure a smooth transition from
one exchange rate to the next. We do not want instability in the
market," he added.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly financial indicators report, the Bank of Uganda
announced that the Shilling had depreciated 6.7 percent against
the Dollar from 1,156 to 1,234 at the end of April this year.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic fall in coffee exports caused by the adverse
weather conditions brought by the El-Nino weather pattern was
blamed for the sharp devaluation of Shilling. Coffee accounts for
60 percent of Uganda's total foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
The official said the government had expected the revenue
collections this year to reach 840 billion Shillings (840 million
Dollars) and now had to adjust it to 810 billion Shillings (810
million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, he said the shortfall will not be carried on to the next
fiscal year since they would contain it within this financial year by
cutting back on expenditure in non-priority areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
