<HEADLINE> Commentary: Who Is Actually Making Nuclear Threat? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The explosion of five nuclear
devices by India last week posed a grave threat to peace and
stability in South Asia and the world, undermining international
efforts for non-proliferation and a complete test ban of nuclear
weapons and arousing strong condemnation world-wide.
</P>
<P>
Seeking to justify their nuclear tests, Indian leaders however
have repeatedly made smearing attacks on China.
</P>
<P>
Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes publicly accused China
of being "India's potential threat number one."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee also claimed that India is
bordered by a country known to have nuclear weapons that invaded
India in 1962 and that despite improved relations with it in the
last decade, an absence of trust persisted because of unsettled
border disputes.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all, China has all along pursued a foreign
policy of peace and friendship. The Chinese government has stated
many times that China's small quantity of nuclear weapons is not
aimed at threatening anyone, but is solely out of the need for
defense. China will never be the first to use nuclear weapons at
any time or under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has signed the Treaty on Non-proliferation
of Nuclear Weapons and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and has
been faithfully fulfilling the obligations of the two treaties.
</P>
<P>
China is a responsible country that keeps its promise on the
issue of nuclear weapons. India's argument that it conducted
nuclear tests because of having a nuclear-equipped neighbor is
totally untenable.
</P>
<P>
As for Vajpayee' claim of China's invasion, historical facts
brook no distortion.
</P>
<P>
It is known to all that after its declaration of independence
in 1950, the Indian government kept pushing forward its northern
boundary and occupied some 90,000 square kilometers of Chinese
territories in between the traditional line in the eastern section
of the borders and the illegal McMahon Line.
</P>
<P>
In October 1962, the Indian government continued to pursue its
policy of expansionism and started a large-scale war of invasion
against China.
</P>
<P>
Driven beyond the limits of forbearance, China's border troops
fought back in self-defense. Even under those circumstances, China
ceased fire and withdrew troops on its own initiative and called
for resumption of negotiations to seek a peaceful end to the
border conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, the Chinese government has persistently worked
for a peaceful resolution of the border issue and taken measures
to improve bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Former Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's visit to China in
1988 and Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to India in 1996
helped to move bilateral relationship in the direction of
friendship and good-neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a series of agreements, including one
on maintaining peace and tranquillity along the line of actual
control on the Chinese-Indian border and another on confidence
building measures in the military field along the line of actual
control in the China-India border areas.
</P>
<P>
These agreements helped to create favorable conditions for the
two countries to enhance mutual trust and resolve their border
issue eventually and reasonably.
</P>
<P>
But at a time when the Sino-Indian relations were being
improved, the Vajpayee government came up with statements on
so-called absence of trust between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Such lame excuses India has made for conducting underground
nuclear tests at the expenses of the overall interest of
Sino-Indian relations have been criticized by the world public
opinion as well as many people of insight in India.
</P>
<P>
"China threat" advocated by the Vajpayee government is not a
fact. But the interference from a group of Indian political
figures with China's internal affairs is a matter of record.
</P>
<P>
India tried in vain to obstruct peaceful liberation of China's
Tibet in the 1950s and allows the Dalai clique to use its
territory to carry out splitting activities against China.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the Dalai clique gave its backing to India's
nuclear tests reflected the sinister relations between the Indian
government and the Dalai clique.
</P>
<P>
India has not only threatened China, but also other neighbors
as well. This cannot be more clearly shown when Vajpayee said
after the nuclear explosion that India had become a country
possessing nuclear weapons and that India would not hesitate to
use nuclear weapons when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts are of the view that with the nuclear
explosion, India seeks to develop nuclear weapons, barge into the
world's club of nuclear powers, and then seek regional hegemony,
which would not only do harm to regional peace and stability, but
also pose a threat to world peace.
</P>
<P>
It has been proved by history that any countries that practised
regional or global hegemony would, contrary to their wishes, get
them nowhere.
</P>
<P>
Peace and development are the two major themes of the world
today, as well as the common wishes of the Chinese and Indian
peoples.
</P>
<P>
Being the two most populous developing countries in the world,
both China and India are facing a huge task of developing their
economies. An improvement in bilateral relations would be in line
with the fundamental interests of the two countries and be
conducive to peace, stability and development in the region and in
the world.
</P>
<P>
We hope that the Indian government would have a clear
understanding of the current trend of development and stop
immediately the development of nuclear weapons, which is against
the wishes of the people the world over.
</P>
<P>
We also hope that the Indian government would stop spreading
rumors and stop doing anything detrimental to the development of
friendly relations between the Indian and Chinese peoples and
instead do something that is favorable to the peace and stability
of South Asia and the world so that the bilateral relations
between the two countries could return to the normal track of
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
