<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Urged to Cut Down Tobacco Co.s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Anti-Tobacco Alliance
has urged the government to urgently curb the excesses of
manufacturers and advertizers of tobacco products in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Media Research, Hugo Odiogor said in a recent
statement that it is appalling the way the Federal Ministry of
Health closes its eye to the massive "catch them young" tactics
of marketing and advertizing companies.
</P>
<P>
Odiogor accused the companies of employing musical jamborees
and social events to recruit young smokers through distribution
of free packets of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to implement the Decree 20 of 1990
which bans smoking in public places and to stop the installation
of cigarette bill boards on school vicinities as a way of
discouraging students smoking.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations Human Index has in the past six years
listed Nigeria as one of the countries with low life expectancy
rate; it is therefore, unthinkable that health authorities would
stick to social habits and culture that further exposes its
population of working age to habits that would further worsen the
situation," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
