<HEADLINE> Lesotho Poll Organizers Vow to Continue Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's Independent
Electoral Commission (IEC) vowed Monday to hold the country's
general election on its due date on Saturday despite opposition
parties' attempt to postpone it.
</P>
<P>
IEC chairman Sekara Mafisa said Monday he would fight with
every legal means against the three main opposition parties,
which applied to the Lesotho high court to have the polls put off
for alleged irregularities.
</P>
<P>
"I am prepared to go to the high court this afternoon to fight
for the Basotho nation. Preparations for these elections are so
much at an advance stage that they cannot be reserved as it will
do great harm to the nation's high spirit," South African Press
Association quoted Mafisa as saying in Maseru, the capital.
</P>
<P>
The court hearing is scheduled for this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The election, the tiny mountain kingdom's third democratic
election since its independence in 1966, is scheduled for May 23.
</P>
<P>
The Basotholand Congress Party, Basotho National Party and the
Marematlou Freedom Party have asked for a court order that the
IEC investigate alleged irregularities, including the fact that
80 percent of the residents of a village was registered as having
been born on a New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
Mafisa said it was disturbing that the opposition leaders were
calling for a postponement without identifying an alternative
election date. "How can they demand an indefinite postponement?"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, he defended the IEC's poll schedule, saying the
parties had been given enough time to inspect the voters' list.
</P>
<P>
He said it was sad that the opposition threatened court action
knowing the IEC was running on a tight time table.
</P>
<P>
Voting has already taken place at Lesotho embassies abroad,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, those involved in the election, including security
forces, government officials and political parties officials,
will vote ahead of the 1.3 million eligible voters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
