<HEADLINE> Roundup: Foreign Envoys Rush to Pakistan After Indian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign envoys have been rushing
here one after another in the past few days for consultations with
the Pakistani leadership on the South Asian situation in the wake
of Indian nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Aziz Al Khawaitar, special advisor to Saudi King Fahd bin
Abdul Aziz, arrived here Monday morning to deliver a message from
the king to Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Foreign Affairs of the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) Sheikh Hamadan bin Zayed will also come here Monday
afternoon to deliver a message from the UAE ruler to the Pakistani
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources say the Saudi and UAE officials are
apparently on an emergency visit to Pakistan to show their
solidarity with Pakistan following a series of nuclear tests
conducted by India last week. Pakistan enjoys very good relations
with both Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Seiichiro Noboru, special envoy of Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, visited here Sunday to urge Pakistan
to show restraint in response to India's nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
These visits are taking place after a high-caliber U.S.
delegation, led by Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, left
Pakistan on Saturday failing to woo Pakistan away from nuclear
tests.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan and some other big powers have been
urging Pakistan to exercise restraint and not to follow India's
suit, indicating that severe sanctions would be imposed on
Pakistan if it also goes nuclear.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a week after the Indian nuclear tests, the Pakistani
government, which is facing mounting pressure at home to make a
"matching response" to India, has been weighing its options very
carefully as how to respond to its arch rival's actions.
</P>
<P>
Reaffirming the solemn pledge not to compromise national
security, Prime Minister Sharif made it clear on Sunday that
Pakistan possesses nuclear capability and can carry out a nuclear
test "within 12 to 24 hours."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan has also declared that his
government has decided to test a nuclear device. "It's a matter of
when, not if... the decision has already been taken by the
cabinet," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the government, as Prime Minister Sharif has said time
and again, will "make no irrevocable decisions in haste. We are
monitoring the sharp reaction toward the Indian nuclear
explosions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
