<HEADLINE> Japanese Paper Blasts Controversial Movie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese newspaper on Monday
criticized the controversial Japanese film "Pride -- the Fatal
Moment" which whitewashes Japan's aggression against neighboring
countries during World War II.
</P>
<P>
"It is unacceptable to put on show the film which distorts
historical facts and damages trust between Japan and its
neighboring countries at a time when Japan needs to deepen
mutually trustful ties with these countries," the International
Trade, a weekly newspaper affiliated with Japan's Association for
Promotion of International Trade, said in a commentary carried on
its latest edition to be published on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan is in a period of learning from history and winning trust
from other Asian countries by making contributions to peace,
stability and economic development in Asia, the commentary
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
But the film will seriously harm the trustful relations between
Japan and its neighboring countries, the article said, adding it
will surely be condemned by the international community.
</P>
<P>
The commentary called on Japan to make efforts to deepen trust
with other countries in the world as the next century approaches.
</P>
<P>
The film, to be put on show later this month, deals with the
trial and last days of General Hideki Tojo, Japan's wartime prime
minister, who was executed as an A-Class war criminal by the
International Military Tribunal for the Far East in November 1948.
</P>
<P>
Distorting historical facts, the film also depicts Japan's
aggression against neighboring countries during World War II as
self-defense and denies Japanese troops' war crimes including the
Nanjing Massacre in which about 300,000 people were slaughtered by
the Japanese army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
