<HEADLINE> Remains of "Salt Man" Put on Display </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 18 (Xinhua) -- On the occasion of the World Museum
and Cultural Heritage Day Monday, Iran put the remains of a "Salt
Man" of 1,700 years ago on display at its National Museum in
downtown Tehran.
</P>
<P>
This is the debut of the remains of the man, known later as the
"Salt Man," since he was found in 1993 during excavations at a
salt mine in Hamzehlou village of Zanjan province, about 300
kilometers west of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition was inaugurated by Iran's Minister of Culture
and Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani. Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami sent a message which was read at the opening
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The remains, including the head and one leg, have been
naturally mummified as a result of lying in salty conditions.
</P>
<P>
After studies on the man's remains and his belongings
discovered, scientists believed that he might be a hunter or a
prince of about 40 years old, who had been wounded for yet unknown
reasons a short while before his death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Army Officer Released by Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A Philippine Army officer, who was
abducted early this month by suspected members of the leftist New
People's Army (NPA), has been released by the rebel group, the
Philippine News Agency said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Army Master Sergeant Ricardo Castro was set free Sunday in
Quezon City, Metro Manila, after 15 days of captivity, the news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
He was turned over by a representative of the National
Democratic Front (NDF), which led the NPA, to representatives of
the International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Castro's release was negotiated by representatives of local
non-governmental organizations and the religious sector.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, a leftist alliance created by the Communist Party of
the Philippines in the late 1960s, has been fighting the
government for decades.
</P>
<P>
The insurgency of the NDF reached its peak in the 1980s with
its armed wing NPA having a membership of more than 20,000. But
the strength of the NDF later weakened considerably due to
military operations and factionalism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
