<HEADLINE> Jordan, U.S. Hold Live-Fire Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States has launched
month-long, live-fire military exercises with Jordan, involving
marines and sailors of the U.S. Navy's 5th fleet, semi-official
Jordan Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a U.S. Defense Department statement issued
Sunday as saying that the joint exercises began Thursday. But it
did not say how many troops of both sides were taking part in the
drill and where it is taking place.
</P>
<P>
Army officials here are not immediately available for comment
on the exercises codenamed "Infinite Moonlight '98."
</P>
<P>
But a similar live-fire mock war last year, involving 500
Americans and a similar number of Jordanians, was held in the
desert town of Qatrana, 120 kilometers south to Amman.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the latest maneuver was designed to
demonstrate U.S. commitment to regional security and increase
cooperation between U.S. amphibious forces and Jordanian armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's official news agency has said that the drill from May
14 to June 16 was held to help raise the efficiency and skills of
Jordanian armed forces, enabling them to gain combat experiences
and learn about advanced and modern military equipment.
</P>
<P>
Since Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994,
Washington has donated 300 million U.S. dollars worth of military
supplies, including F-16 jet fighters, tanks and helicopters, to
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. forces have conducted joint exercises with several
Arab countries, including Egypt, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Jordan.
</P>
</TEXT>
