<HEADLINE> Thefts of Cultural Relics Increasing, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Smuggling and illegal trading in
cultural relics are on the rise and there is an increase in thefts
committed by crime rings, according to a senior Chinese official
in charge of cultural relics protection.
</P>
<P>
Dong Baohua, vice director of the State Bureau of Cultural
Relics, said there are criminal groups at home and abroad who
conspire to steal cultural relics according to demand on the
international market.
</P>
<P>
The thefts were carried out in a well-organized and planned way
and target museum treasures, Dong said here today while attending
activities to mark the 21st International Museum Day which has the
theme of "fighting against illegal trafficking and trading of
cultural relics."
</P>
<P>
He called for increasing the public's awareness to protect
cultural relics as well as intensifying law-enforcement efforts.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of officials in cultural relics departments and museum
staff workers are hitting the streets, offering consultations and
distributing leaflets on the laws and regulations on cultural
relics protection.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has 100 museums which receive more than 40 million
visitors each year. 
</P>
