<HEADLINE> India Offers Early Dialogue with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Chairman of India's
Planning Commission Jaswant Singh said Monday that India had
offered dialogue with the United States and other western
countries over the recent five nuclear tests in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. White House has said that India had engaged in
deception as it carried out a surreptitious nuclear weapons
program and conducted five successful tests.
</P>
<P>
"I think, (there has been) on the part of the Indians a
deliberate campaign of deception since March. They have said
they'd exercise restraint," U.S. National Security Advisor Sandy
Berger said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meeting foreign correspondents here, Jaswant Singh said there
was no panic about U.S. sanctions and asserted that India would
meet them effectively.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the sanctions are estimated at 20 billion
U.S. dollars. India would have to be depending on selling its gold
reserves to stem the effects of sanctions. Jaswant, however,
described the reports as "speculative".
</P>
<P>
New Delhi was ready to engage in a meaningful discussions with
key interlocutors on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT)
issue, he said. He did not elaborate on meaningful discussions on
the issue. The Vajpayee government has rejected the present form
of CTBT.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether India's economy would be adversely affected
as a result of the sanctions and the huge amounts spent on nuclear
projects, Jaswant Singh said that the country's nuclear program
would not be at the cost of the Indian economy. He parried
questions on any substantial hike in the defense budget or
recasting of the general budget.
</P>
<P>
Indian senior officials have time and again warned that the
future budget, to be presented to Parliament on June 1, would be
"tough". Prices of petroleum products might be raised in the
budget, etc.. 
</P>
</TEXT>
