<HEADLINE> Unofficial Diplomacy Needed to Advance Friendship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese People's Association
for Friendship with Foreign Countries (CPAFFC) will be more active
in developing its relations with organizations in other countries
to advance friendship between China and the rest of the world, a
CPAFFC official said today.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1954, the CPAFFC is intended to enhance mutual
understanding and friendship and to promote economic, cultural,
scientific and technological cooperation between China and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
CPAFFC Vice-President Chen Haosu told a news briefing today
that his organization has so far established cooperative relations
with 364 unofficial organizations in 115 countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 821 Chinese cities have established sister-city
relationships with cities in other countries.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the CPAFFC will hold its seventh council
meeting on May 20-22, during which members of the council will
discuss ways to advance unofficial diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
The term of the seventh council is from 1998 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
The unofficial diplomacy, an important part of China's
diplomacy as a whole, has made a major contribution to the
development of relations between China and the rest of the world,
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Chen called the CPAFFC the ambassador to spread seeds of
friendship, and said that the seventh council meeting will usher
in a new chapter in the 21st century for the CPAFFC to advance the
cause of friendship.  
</P>
