<HEADLINE> Cocaine Seizure in Namibia Surges Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 38 kilogram of
cocaine was confiscated in Namibia last year, which was more than
sixfold of the amount seized in 1996, a Namibian paper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The commanding officer of the Namibian police drug law
enforcement unit, Lousi Mensah, told the high court in Windhoek
on Friday that the amount of cocaine seized in the country had
"increased heavily" every year in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, 595 gram of cocaine was confiscated in Namibia, and
the amount rose tenfold to 5,953 gram in 1996 and further shot up
to 38,552 gram last year, Mensah said.
</P>
<P>
The cocaine seized last year was estimated to be worth at
least 13.49 million Namibian Dollars (2.7 million U.S. Dollars),
Mensah told judges during a trial of a Nigerian and two Namibians
charged with drug dealing or possession.
</P>
<P>
Cocaine smugglers were increasingly using Namibia for the
transit of drugs, mostly to South Africa, where drug dealers find
a larger, more affluent market, he said.
</P>
<P>
The cocaine found in Namibia originates mostly from South
America, Mensah said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
