<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac: France Sees Eye to Eye With Egypt on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 18 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac has
said Cairo and Paris share identical views toward the Mideast
peace process and will work together to save the peace drive.
</P>
<P>
In an article exclusively contributed to the Egyptian Al Ahram
newspaper Monday, Chirac said there should be a just and
comprehensive peace in the region, which is the guarantee of
development and security.
</P>
<P>
It is the right of the Palestinian people to have an
independent state, Chirac said, adding that in return for full
security Israel must give back the Golan Heights to Syria, and
Lebanon likewise must enjoy full stability and sovereignty over
its southern territory.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks on the Palestinian track have been stalled
since March 1997 when Israel began construction of a Jewish
housing project in Arab East Jerusalem, and negotiations on the
Syrian and Lebanese tracks are on ice since February 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The land-for-peace formula is the sole way for reaching
positive outcome," Chirac said in the article, which comes out
just as Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's starts his three-day
visit to Paris.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's talks in France will focus on methods of confronting
impediments obstructing peace efforts in the forms of extremism
and intransigence, Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
"France, while understanding Israel's desire for peace, sees as
a must that Tel Aviv respects the timetable of its troop
redeployment in the West Bank in order to ease up tension in the
region," he added.
</P>
<P>
Calling settlement-building in the West Bank and East Jerusalem
an illegal act, Chirac rejected any move aimed at changing the
status quo of Jerusalem and any prejudgement of the final status
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Chirac are expected to issue a "special statement"
on the Mideast peace process in Paris, outlining their
visualization of the next steps to spare the region a whirlpool of
violence and to get the peace process out of impasse.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency here said the two leaders will call
for adherence to the U.N. Security Council resolutions,
continuation of the land-for-peace principle, implementation of
the signed agreements and resumption of talks on the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks from where they stopped.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders have often exchanged visits. Chirac visited
Egypt three times in 1996 while Mubarak toured Paris last summer.
</P>
<P>
But Mubarak's trip this time is of particular significance in
view of the 14-month deadlock in Palestinian-Israeli peace-making.
</P>
<P>
Chirac has said he shared Arab frustration over the pace of
peace talks under the right-wing Israeli government of Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say France's historical ties with many countries in
the Middle East make it an ideal advocate of Arab political and
economic concerns in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Reveals Child Labor Situation in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- About 17 percent of child workers in
Bangladesh have to work for 15 to 19 hours a day and up to 65
percent for nine to 14 hours, according to a joint study by the
International Labor Organization and the U.N. Children's Fund.
</P>
<P>
The study, entitled "Child Labor Situation in Bangladesh: a
Rapid Assessment" also showed that 14 percent of child laborers in
the country work for five to eight hours everyday while 4 percent
one to four hours as part-time workers, the independent United
News of Bangladesh (UNB) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the study did not mention the total number of child
laborers in this South Asian country.
</P>
<P>
The children were found "to do almost all kinds of jobs that
adults do in urban areas, and children are involved in 300 types
of economic activities while the number is 90 in rural areas,"
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
But, the study said their income is very low. The average
monthly income of self-employed children is 793 taka (17.2 U.S.
dollars) while that for children employed by others is only 363
taka (about 7.9 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some 27 types of jobs the child laborers are doing have been
rated as hazardous for children, the study stated.
</P>
<P>
Their jobs include those exposing them to flame, chemical
substances, gas, fume and dust, handling garbage, high-speed
machinery and sharp equipment and working with electricity,
extreme heat or cold, insufficient light, heavy load, stressful
working conditions and non-stop working with ice and water, the
study observed.
</P>
<P>
The study further said about 48 percent of working children
never attended schools, 43 percent ended school earlier and only 9
percent of them continued to attend school or got some form of
education provided by the non-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
When these children were asked whether they would be interested
in getting enrolled in school if opportunities were available, 74
percent replied in the affirmative, the study added.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has almost eliminated child labor in ready-made
garment industries and it plans to abolish it in hazardous
industries by the turn of this century and all forms of child
labor by the year 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
