<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Begins Military Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli army has begun a
monumental reshuffle of its General Staff following the
appointment of Major General Shaul Mofaz as the new chief last
week, Israel Radio reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The army announced six top appointments late last night.
Maj. Gen. Uzi Dayan, head of the Central Command, was promoted to
replace Maj. Gen. Mofaz as deputy chief of the General Staff. His
post in the Central Command was given to military intelligence
leader Maj. Gen. Moshe Yaalon.
</P>
<P>
Dayan, 50, the nephew of former military leader Moshe Dayan who
led the Israeli army in the 1967 Middle East War, participated in
peace talks with the Palestinians and with Syria and helped
formulate the interim agreements with the Palestinian National
Authority while he was head of the army's planning branch.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Maj. Gen. Yaalon, a veteran paratrooper and
commando, surprised some Israelis because he was widely assumed to
be named head of the Northern Command.
</P>
<P>
But military experts said that he was the best person for his
new position because he knows very well the situation in the West
Bank since he was in charge of the Israeli army in the areas in
1992. They believe that the Central Command, instead of the
Northern Command, has become the most sensitive front.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four-year-old Maj. Gen. Gaby Ashkenazy was appointed
head of the Northern Command to replace Maj. Gen. Amiram Levine,
who has been named deputy head of the secret agency Mossad.
</P>
<P>
A former commander of the Golani Brigade as well as head of
Israel Defense Force (IDF) forces in Lebanon, most of Ashkenazy's
career has been spent in the North.
</P>
<P>
The place of Maj. Gen. Yaalon as Head of Intelligence was
given to Maj. Gen. Amos Malka, 45. Appointed head of the Ground
Corps Command in 1996, he has been exclusively in the Armored
Corps in his 26 years of military career and never held an
intelligence command. Veteran Maj. Gen. Moshe Ivry-Sukenik would
replace him as head of the Ground Corps Command.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Brig. Gen. Yaacov Amidror, military aide to Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, was named commander of military
colleges. He becomes the first observant member of the General
Staff, aside from the chief chaplain, in over two decades.
</P>
<P>
This was the first round of reshuffles expected in the General
Staff, Israel Radio said. 12 of its 18 positions are expected to
be reassigned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
