<HEADLINE> Central China City Attracting Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Wuhan, capital of central China's
Hubei Province, has made actual use of 4.38 billion U.S. dollars
of overseas investment since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 150 of the world's top 500 multinational
firms have made inspection tours to Wuhan, an advantageously
positioned city commonly known as a "thoroughfare linking nine
provinces," and 40 multinational companies have come to invest in
this central Chinese city, said Sun Huaiyu, head of the city's
overseas investment affairs office.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment opportunities are now available in the
city's general processing industrial business, infrastructure,
basic industry, agriculture and high-tech industrial enterprises,
with the ways of using them including starting joint ventures,
using foreign governmental loans, performing processing and
assembly, using loans of international financial organizations,
international leasing and compensation trade.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the city has used overseas investment to help
complete construction of a number of major urban infrastructure
projects, including a new international airport, an expressway to
the airport, a highway bridge across the Yangtze River, which
separates Wuhan into three parts -- Wuchang, Hankou and Hanyang.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
