<HEADLINE> Northwestern Chinese Province Using International Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province in northwestern
China is making an effort to increase contacts with the outside
world to get more international aid for its economy.
</P>
<P>
The most recent sources are Canada, Germany, Australia, and
Japan, with more than 20 projects, worth over 100 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The province managed 58 projects with free foreign government
or organization aid last year, worth 35 million U.S. dollars that
included World Food Program agriculture and poverty relief
projects, UNICEF social development projects in impoverished
areas, and an EU irrigation training center.
</P>
<P>
The province has established long-term relations with the
UNDP, UNICEF, and United Nations Fund for Population Activities
for poverty relief and education in poor areas, using agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Germany and the Netherlands joined the effort by
provided aid for drinking water, healthcare, technical training
for ethnic minority women, and handicapped children.
</P>
<P>
Government departments have increased their efforts in aid
applications and implementation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
