<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Prime Minister Strongly Committed to Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
said here Monday his government has made a strong-willed
commitment to reform programs, which aim to bail the country out
of economic woes and restore investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
"We know that we are still at the early stages of a painful,
but constructive reform process," said the Prime Minister, who
delivered a keynote address here Monday at the fifth annual Credit
Lyonnais Securities Asia (CLSA) Investors' Forum.
</P>
<P>
Chuan Leekpai told more than 1,000 global investors: "When my
government assumed office last November, our first priority was to
stabilize the value of our currency and quickly restore confidence
in our economy."
</P>
<P>
Rapid action was taken on three fronts -- to stabilize the
Baht, facilitate the rolling-over of private foreign debt, and
reform financial institutions, said the 60-year-old Prime
Minister, who has been involved in politics for 29 years.
</P>
<P>
The Thai currency devalued by 46 percent to 45 Baht to one
U.S. dollar in nine months after the Asian financial crisis first
stroke Thailand in July last year. Thanks to the strict
implementation of a comprehensive reform package, including
cutting public spending, raising taxes and curbing inflation, the
Baht now has been stable at just below 40 Baht to the green back.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government also took decisive action to reform its
financial sector -- closing down over half of finance companies,
taking over four ailing banks, tackling non-performing loans, and
enhancing transparent regulation.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister laid out three challenges to the recovery
of the Thai economy: accelerating export growth, expediting
corporate restructuring, and committing to real reforms and good
governance.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of this year, exports of Tailand rose
substantially in Baht terms, but fell by 2.7 percent in U.S. dollar
terms. But the prime minister predicted that measures to ease the
liquidity problem would help boost exports in the second half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
On corporate restructuring, Chuan Leekpai said: "The best way
to accomplish this task is to maintain an open economy, subject to
the full forces of competition." Restrictions on foreign
ownership have been relaxed, allowing foreign investors to acquire
majority stakes in domestic financial institutions for up to ten
years, and privatization of a broad range of state enterprises is
also under way, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed the importance of clean
governance, saying that his government is committed to effective
anti-corruption measures, transparent decision-making, prevention
of conflict of interest, and appropriate checks and balances to
ensure full accountability.
</P>
<P>
He finally expressed strong confidence in the recovery of the
Thai economy. "A road to full recovery will never be straight and
smooth," the prime minister said, adding "we do not believe in
miracles -- just plain hard work, with a dose of determination."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
