<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Malaysia Into Top Four at Thomas Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Both defending champions
Indonesia and four-time winners Malaysia qualified for the
semi-finals after their respective second Group B matches at the
20th Thomas Cup Badminton Finals here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia won over South Korea 4-1, losing the second doubles
match due to what the team manager later described as "mental
problem" of one player.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, four-time champions which failed though to make the
top four at the last championships here, whitewashed lowly-rated
Netherlands 5-0.
</P>
<P>
With two victories each, Indonesia and Malaysia are now in an
unbeatable position for taking the top two places of Group B. The
two teams are to meet each other on Wednesday to decide which will
be the group winners.
</P>
<P>
"We did what we'd expected of us. One Ewe Hock did quite well
in the first singles today, which gave Malaysia a good start,"
said Malaysia's head coach Morten Frost, who is from Denmark.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia is a very strong team and it gives all the other
teams a lot of pressure. If everything is going to work, they can
take two points from the doubles," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I'll be very happy if we can split a doubles," he added.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy with our team's performance here today. Losing the
second doubles, due to mental problem of one of the players, means
that we had to make more efforts to improve," said Indonesian team
manager Agus Wirahadikusumah.
</P>
<P>
He predicted Wednesday's tie against Malaysia to be "very
tight." But he declined to say who are to be fielded for the last
group match.
</P>
<P>
"We never rely on the selection of players to win matches. It
is the players' performance that matters. We will field the best
team in best performance in the semi-finals, either against China
or Denmark," he added.
</P>
<P>
In Group A actions Monday evening, China will play Hong Kong,
China, while Denmark will take on Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
