<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Magnet for Foreign Investors in South China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Dongguan city in south China's
Guangdong Province has attracted more foreign investors in
developing export-oriented agriculture in recent years.
</P>
<P>
An official from the city government said that exports of farm
products from Dongguan exceeded 100 million U.S. dollars last
year, twice that of 1990.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, investors from more than 10 countries and regions
such as the United States, Thailand, Singapore, and Hong Kong
established 151 agricultural enterprises in Dongguan with an
investment exceeding one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Situated in the center of the Pearl River Delta area, Dongguan
was formerly an agricultural county. To bring its advantage into
full play, the city government set up a special agency for
the introduction of foreign investment in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Now, agriculture in Dongguan has become a magnet for foreign
investors, who also brought with them advanced technology, funds
and markets. Agricultural products such as flowers, vegetables,
and fruits are exported to Europe, the United States, and
Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Urges G8 to Write off Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
has appealed to Group-8 donors to write off the debts of the
heavily indebted African countries, Zambia Daily Mail reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon Sunday in Windhoek, capital of Namibia,
Chiluba said the debts had a lot of negative impact on the
African economies.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who went to Windhoek to attend a three-day Southern
African Economic Summit which starts Monday, stressed that the
amount of money Zambia spends on servicing its debt denied the
country the chance to plow back the resources into development.
</P>
<P>
As long as the G8 do not write off the debts, African
economies will remain poor, said the Zambian president, adding
that the heavy debt which has reached 7.2 billion U.S. Dollars by
the end of 1997 has been eating Zambia's resources for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
When asked on the future of Zambia's two largest copper mines,
Nchanga and Nkana, which is going to be privatized, Chiluba said
that his country has the best grade of copper in the world and
there is no doubt that the remaining mines will also be sold.
</P>
<P>
He noted that he is interested in seeing that only good
investors come to Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
