<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultivating Rice Seedlings In "Workshop" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Some farmers in central-south
China are in the process of phasing out the centuries-old method
of cultivating rice seedlings in paddy fields, and turning instead
to "workshops".
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the town of Quantangzi in Hunan Province now buy
their rice seedlings from a local greenhouse where agronomists
develop seedlings assembly fashion instead of on fields.
</P>
<P>
A conveyor belt moves along slowly and soil, seeds, and water
being added evenly in a process that takes only about a minute,
and in 10 days, the seedlings are ready for sowing.
</P>
<P>
The "ready-made" seedlings save farmers a lot of trouble and
are fairly high in quality, one farmer said.
</P>
<P>
The local agricultural technology station has signed an
agreement with farmers that said it will pay for any losses caused
by faulty seedlings.
</P>
<P>
The province has set up four of these "workshops" as part of a
commercialization process, and this year plans to use the
factory-produced seedlings on more than 300,000 hectares of paddy
fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
