<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ruling Party Factionalism Said to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The internal fighting and factions
within the ruling Zanu (PF) party is a national crisis that
should be resolved as it affects the whole country, a senior
Trade Union official has said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions Morgan
Tsvangirai said Zanu as a ruling party led the country through
its policies and ideologies, hence the nation could not afford to
have open hostility and factions within the party.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing a University of Zimbabwe student
representative council-organized meeting on tackling the current
national socio-economic and political crisis facing the country
at the end of last week, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the internal explosion within Zanu where people are
creating factions to the point that there is no direction and yet
this is a ruling party is a national crisis."
</P>
<P>
On the country's economic crisis and escalating cost of
living, he said Zimbabwe was slowly moving toward a serious state
of decay mainly due to political discontent within the ruling
party.
</P>
<P>
"This crisis is not a laughing matter, we need to build a
Zimbabwe which is not divided but one that moves toward national
integration, work out logistics that will see prices of basic
commodities going down," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come for decisions to be made to improve the
country's economy and the president cannot avoid this," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there was also need for a national anti-corruption
commission to be set up to look into several senior government
officials and ministers and their activities with a view to
recovering national resources that were squandered to benefit a
few individuals.
</P>
<P>
At the same occasion, member of parliament Margaret Dongo said
Zimbabwe should not treat constitutional reform as the only
remedy to the current socio-economic and political crisis.
</P>
<P>
She said under the new constitution, parliament should have
the power to pass a vote of no-confidence in the president with
all MPs being democratically elected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
