<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Helping Small State Firms in Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A marriage between the private sector
and small state-owned businesses is now in vogue in the capital of
China's Shaanxi Province, where 151 private enterprises have got
involved in restructuring state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
They use stock transfers, acquisitions, leasing, and management
agreements. This practice started when the provincial government
set up policies to revitalize small state businesses and to
encourage the non-state sector to participate.
</P>
<P>
Combining state firms' resources and equipment with private
businesses' greater flexibility and awareness of market
competition has had some successful results.
</P>
<P>
Two private pharmaceutical companies, for example, put 5.58
million yuan into a state-owned pharmaceutical factory in 1996 to
form the Shaanxi Dongsheng Pharmaceutical Co. Ltd, which had
profits of 10 million yuan last year, making it one the province's
best pharmaceutical companies and a source of employment for 180
laid-off employees of the state-owned enterprise.
</P>
<P>
The city has more than 10,000 small state-owned businesses,
most of them troubled by poor performance and some even teetering
on the brink of bankruptcy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
