<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 08:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Army Chief Leaves for Russia for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Chief of General Staff
Ismail Hakki Karadayi left here for Moscow Monday on a five-day
visit to try to talk the Russians out of a missile sale to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
According to the semi-official Anatolia News Agency, Haradayi's
visit was also aimed at cementing Turkish-Russian military ties.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Karadayi will do his utmost to dissuade
Russia to go ahead with its S-300 missile deal with Cyprus, which
could become a potential flashpoint in the region if handled
improperly.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials have said the missiles will be delivered to
Cyprus in mid-August and argued that Turkey should withdraw its
40,000-strong troops from the divided island first.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government decided last year to purchase Russian
S-300 surface-to-air missile system to upgrade its defense
capability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reacted strongly to the deal and threatened to block
the delivery of the missiles and, if that fails, to destroy them.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed on the island and took over the the northern third in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has so far maintained around 40,000 troops in northern
Cyprus, which was declared unilaterally by Turkish Cypriots in
1983 "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," recognized only by
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish army chief, in addition, will discuss with Russian
officials alleged Moscow's support to Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party, which has been fighting Ankara since 1984 for the
establishment of an independent Kurdish state in southeast
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
