<HEADLINE> Uganda to Spend 4b Shillings on Rural Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has said the government is to spend 4 billion Uganda Shillings (4
million U.S. Dollars) on road maintenance in rural districts.
</P>
<P>
Museveni was quoted by Monday's New Vision newspaper as saying
the money would keep at least 75 percent of the feeder roads in
good conditions.
</P>
<P>
In a speech read by the Second Deputy Prime Minister Moses Ali
in Kampala Friday, Museveni attributed the bad road conditions to
lack of road maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The president urged district officials to cooperate so that a
good road network can be built.
</P>
<P>
"Even if you are not prepared to cooperate in other areas, I
urge you to at least cooperate in the road sector area. Plan,
construct and repair your roads jointly," he said.
</P>
<P>
The construction, rehabilitation and maintenance of roads is
the legal obligation of district councils, he added.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains brought by the El-Nino weather phenomenon
destroyed many feeder roads across the country, hindering the
local produce from reaching the market. Now many feeder roads are
still characterized by poor or non-existent drainage and broken
culverts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
