<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Meet Revenue Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will be the sole member
state of the East African Cooperation (EAC) which is set to win
its revenue collection target for the 1997/98 fiscal year ending
June.
</P>
<P>
Both Uganda and Tanzania -- the other two EAC members -- say
they will not be able to make it mainly due to the heavy El Nino
rains, the East African weekly newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's projected revenue for the year totals 160 billion
Shillings (2.7 billion U.S. Dollars), compared with the 146
billion (2.4 billion Dollars) collected in 1996/97.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA)'s Commissioner-General John
Msafari said it is new measures to curb dumping and diversions of
transit goods such as sugar, textiles and tyres, onto the
domestic market that boost Kenya's revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
Kenya introduced cash bonds for goods in transit last year.
The move was widely criticized by the Ugandan business community,
but has reduced the malpractices and boosted revenue collection,
Msafari said last week in Entebbe, Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Counting on improvements in revenue administration and
widening the tax base, Kenya has further emphasized customs and
excise duties as the main areas of revenue collection, he said at
a meeting of the EAC revenue authority bosses.
</P>
<P>
And unlike Uganda and Tanzania which rely heavily on
agriculture, Kenya has a booming financial market (which it taxes
heavily) and a lucrative insurance business, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Of Uganda's projected total revenue of 840 billion Ugandan
Shillings (700 million Dollars), 829 billion Ugandan Shillings
was expected from taxes accruing from improved tax administration
by the Uganda Revenue Authority for the year.
</P>
<P>
The balance of 11 billion Ugandan Shillings was expected from
appropriations in aid.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania could not meet the projected revenue of 631 billion
Tanzanian Shillings (949 million Dollars) for the 1997/98 year,
although it has imposed high tax rates on agricultural products,
including an export tax of two percent stamp duty, said Tanzania
Revenue Authority boss M.E. Sanare.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's total revenue in the 1996/97 fiscal year was 550
billion Tanzanian Shillings (827 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sanare blamed the adverse weather as the main reason behind
his body's failure to meet the target.
</P>
<P>
"It is becoming difficult to achieve the targets because of El
Nino," he said.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rains in the region since last October caused damage
to the railway linking land-locked Uganda to the Port of
Dar-es-Salaam, thus leading to a substantial decrease in Ugandan
cargo, denying Tanzania Harbors Authority and Tanzania Railways
Corporation revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sees Sharp Rise in Cement Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Numerous construction projects in
Nigeria may soon ground to a halt following an acute shortage of
cement which has suddenly shot up the price of a 50kg bag of the
product by 66.7 percent, the Business Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the weekly, dealers in Lagos, the business center
of the country, blamed the hike on a sudden increase in demand
which has made it difficult for both local producers and
importers to ensure adequate supply to the market.
</P>
<P>
The price of cement is even higher in the national capital
Abuja where the on-going boom in construction projects have
caused massive diversion of cement from other parts of the
country but the supply is still far from enough.
</P>
<P>
The work on the completion of many abandoned building projects
across the country and the numerous road construction work going
on in Abuja and other parts of the country also contribute to the
nationwide short supply of cement.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources at the same time also blamed the inability of
Nigeria's six functional cement manufacturing companies to meet
the sudden jump in demand.
</P>
<P>
According to the weekly, there were fears last week that the
federal government's ambitious housing plan and that of the
states may suffer a serious setback if the dangerous trend in the
cement market is not rectified immediately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
