<HEADLINE> Kenya to Ban Chemical Fishing in L. Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has embarked
on a campaign to stamp out chemical fishing in Lake Victoria to
save the country's fishing industry worth five billion Shillings
(83.3 million U.S. Dollars) per year.
</P>
<P>
The use of a chemical known locally as "Ambus" to harvest fish
in the lake is likely to complicate the crisis facing the
industry, following a ban on east African fresh fish exports to
European Union market, the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Governmental chemists in Nairobi have found the fish to be
contaminated with the "Ambus" chemical and declared it unfit for
human consumption. Some fishermen have also been arrested on
suspicion of using the chemical.
</P>
<P>
Investigations have established that "Ambus" originated from
Uganda, said fishing expert Mathias Waful.
</P>
<P>
Fi;4ermen sprayed the chemical in water and returned five
hours later to collect their catch, which would be floating on
the surface of the lake, the second largest fresh water lake in
the world, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
