<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biotech in Silicon Valley Still Hot for Venture Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Biotech and medical companies
in Silicon Valley received almost 100 million U.S. dollars of
venture capital in the first quarter this year, according to a
survey by the consulting firm Price Waterhouse.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the sector, which has been a hot area for venture
capital, drew 532 million dollars. In 1996, it received 377
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of total venture dollars devoted to biotech in
Silicon Valley has declined from 25.7 percent in 1994 to less than
15 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
But analysts say that the relative decline reflects the boom in
information technology, not a turning away from biotech.
</P>
<P>
To attract venture capitalists, biotech companies have to prove
not only the effectiveness of a new technology or a new drug, but
also their ability to contain costs in health care.
</P>
<P>
Two of the hottest areas of interest for venture capitalists
are medical devices and the so-called "tools" such as databases
and research software.
</P>
<P>
Two companies, which received a total of 27 million dollars,
are developing micro-catheters to diagnose and treat heart
disorders and bypass devices used through the skin.
</P>
<P>
Venture capitalists have been even more enthusiastic about the
marriage of computer technology with biomedicine.
</P>
<P>
Among those receiving the big money are companies which, helped
along by the Human Genome Project, attempt to offer a range of
databases and ways of analyzing disease.
</P>
<P>
The project is meant to identify the roughly 100,000 human
genes. Its ultimate promise is to enable a doctor to prescribe
treatment knowing particular genetic structure of the patient. But
before researchers arrive at that point, a great deal of work must
be done. Now by using existing databases and the computational
programs offered by these companies, a researcher can cut the time
needed to design tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa, US Corporate Fraud Rates Highest: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Africa and the United States have
the highest rates of corporate fraud in the world, a survey by
Ernst &AMP; Young, an international management firm, has shown.
</P>
<P>
The rate in the two regions was pegged at 88 percent of the
organizations polled, while 30 percent of the respondents had
suffered five or more frauds in the previous year, the East
African weekly quoted the survey as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, released this month, is based on questionnaires
sent to senior executives in 11,000 large organizations in 32
countries. Kenya and South Africa were the only African states
covered in the survey.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the organizations interviewed had been
defrauded in the last 12 months, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
A key finding was that 84 percent of the worst frauds
worldwide were by employees, usually those who had served for
five years or more. The worst culprits were in management.
</P>
<P>
The high incidence of employee fraud suggested inadequate
internal controls in many organizations.
</P>
<P>
Examples from Denmark and Southeast Asia showed that a
thorough understanding of an organization's entire business
operations by its directors could help curb the incidence of
fraud.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to common opinion, fraud is not something peculiar to
banking. More than 60 percent of the worst case frauds over one
million U.S. Dollars were outside the sector.
</P>
<P>
Of the 628 million Dollars lost in "worst case frauds" in the
previous year, only 485 million Dollars was recovered, and that
included insurance recoveries.
</P>
<P>
The main areas of fraud are listed as misappropriations of
cash and assets and purchasing fraud.
</P>
<P>
Reliance on proper internal controls and internal audits are
listed by the survey as the two top effective ways of preventing
and detecting fraud. External audits, change of management and
reliance on internal "whistle-blowers" are ranked far lower in
the ladder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Ethnic Areas Looking For Grain Self-sufficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region
in southwestern China is planning to produce 18 million tons of
grain by the end of the century to become self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
The region has only 0.05 hectare of farmland per capita but
produced 16.7 million tons of grain last year, or 350 kilograms
for each person, basically making it self-sufficient in grain, but
it still buys fodder grain elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
It has formulated 150 policies and regulations in the past few
years to promote agricultual production and increased the area
planted in grain from 3.53 million hectares in 1993 to 3.73
million ha in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It has also spent at least 6 billion yuan in the past decade to
help solve food problems in impoverished areas, and in the process
reduced the number of poor people to 3.6 million, compared with 15
million in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
The region has been successful in projects that increase grain
production. A dry growing technique, for example, was used on 1.3
million hectares last year, and helped raise per-hectare grain
output by 630 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
If a poor region like Guangxi can be practically
self-sufficient in its grain supply, then China as a whole can
feed itself, says Hu Angang, an economist at the Chinese Academy
of Social Sciences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
