<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Herdsmen Embrace Modern Animal Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Naranchimug, a 54-year-old Mongolian
herdswoman in China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, begins her
day by using artificial insemination techniques to collect semen
from four rams to inseminate 20 ewes.
</P>
<P>
This results in an improved species of sheep, each of which
produces three kilograms more of wool, worth an additional 100
yuan. The region has imported 23 new varieties of fine breeding
stock, which they use for 63 percent of their herd, as Inner
Mongolia moves faster in the direction of modern animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
An embryo implantation technique has been used on 80 percent of
China's cattle and 85 percent of its sheep, and the region has
shipped frozen sperm of beef cattle to 12 provinces.
</P>
<P>
To increase the use of modern animal husbandry techniques, the
region has tried to implement industrial management of animal
husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Te Yuanda Beef Cattle Development Co. of Ongniud Banner, for
example, spent 62 million yuan on a beef freezing and processing
plant with an annual capacity of 30,000 head of cattle and 100,000
sheep. 
</P>
