<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protection of Yellow River's Source Considered Urgent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Pictures taken by satellite in the
1970s, '80s and '90s reveal that large areas of grassland at the
Yellow River's source have been taken over by sand, according to
today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, China's second longest, has its source in
northwestern Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
People can easily see that the color of the region has turned
from green in the 1970s to yellow on today's pictures, a result of
ecological deterioration, reported the country's leading newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Due to climatic changes, over-harvesting of trees, excessive
washing for gold and lack of funds for grassland development, the
ecological environment at the river's source has deteriorated
quickly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The paper said yearly desertification along the river source
has increased by 20 percent, compared with only 3.9 percent in the
1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
And environmental deterioration has also contributed to
frequent stoppages at the river's lower sections.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that serious water shortages and soil
erosion there had caused a reduction of farmland and intensified
droughts, which had an impact on the life of local families. Sixty
percent of the province's 669,000 poor people live in desertified
areas.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the State Environmental Protection
Administration as saying that, due to harsh natural conditions on
the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, known as "the roof of the world", it's
very hard to restore the ecological balance once it has been
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Experts urged setting up a station along the river source for
ecological change reporting, while excessive logging of tress,
digging of herbs, especially hunting and washing for gold should
be strictly prohibited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breakthrough in Genes Identification Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian scientists announced
here Monday that crops could provide the raw materials needed to
make industrial chemicals and polymers, such as plastics, thanks
to the genes identified by Australian, Swedish and English
scientists.
</P>
<P>
"We have identified genes which when introduced into plants
could see the plants operating as mini factories and offering an
alternative to petrochemical oils," said Dr. Allan Green from
Australia's leading research body the Commonwealth Scientific,
Industrial Research Organization (CSIRO).
</P>
<P>
The possibilities are immense: Components of detergents, nylon,
glue, paints, lubricants, plastics could all be produced from
plants, rather than fossil materials. Plants could provide a
renewable, biodegradable source of these high-value speciality
products, Green said on behalf of the Australian, Swedish and
English team.
</P>
<P>
"Raw materials used to make polymers and speciality chemicals
are modified forms of fatty acids," he explained in a media
release.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, these modified fatty acids are produced from
non-renewable petroleum or by chemical processing of vegetable
oils."
</P>
<P>
"We have identified genes from wild plants which carry out
these modifications inside the plant" without any chemical
processing and polluting waste, he added.
</P>
<P>
"These genes can now be transferred to our major oilseed crops
to create highly productive, biodegradable and renewable sources
of these raw materials."
</P>
<P>
"The isolation of these two genes means that we have
accomplished the first important step toward producing oilseeds
with high yields of important fatty acids."
</P>
<P>
One gene identified produces an enzyme responsible for
creating epoxy fatty acids, the major components in the production
of polymers, used for products such as araldite.
</P>
<P>
The other gene is responsible for a different enzyme which
produces acetylenic fatty acids, important for the synthesis of
speciality chemicals, high quality surface coatings and
lubricants.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time in the world anyone has isolated a
gene responsible for the production of an acetylenic compound.
Nobody even knew that such a gene existed before our work
started," said Dr. Sten Stymne of the Swedish University of
Agricultural Science.
</P>
<P>
The researchers transferred the genes into Arabidopsis, a
plant often used as a model by scientists because of its short
life cycle and well understood genetics and produced plants
containing significant levels of either epoxy or acetylenic fatty
acids in their seeds.
</P>
<P>
"The genes we identified come from wild plants not suitable for
farming because of their characteristics such as low yields, so we
are introducing these genes into oilseed plants," Green said.
</P>
<P>
This research has revealed a family of enzymes that perform a
range of chemical modifications to fatty acids and the knowledge
should enable the team to isolate other genes from the family and
further expand the types of oils produced in plants.
</P>
<P>
He said there is still substantial work to be done before
plants producing high levels of these fatty acids are widely
available.
</P>
<P>
An article on the achievement will be published soon by the
U.S. magazine Science, a CSIRO spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
