<HEADLINE> Foreign Portfolio Investments Swell in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Despite the unrest in Indonesia and
the looming political uncertainty in the Philippines, renewed
confidence in the Philippine economy has pushed up portfolio
investments in the country's financial market.
</P>
<P>
Foreign portfolio investments in the country reached 425
million U.S. dollars in the first three months of this year, up 8
percent from the year-ago level, the Philippine News Agency
reported Monday, citing a recent report from the Central Bank of
the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of these investments were spent in purchasing
government securities, equities and bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
Senior economist Gilbert Garchitorena was quoted as saying that
owing to the inflows of portfolio investments, the local composite
index at the local bourses exceeded a seven-month high of 2,311
points.
</P>
<P>
The rising portfolio investments in the country are an
indication that foreign portfolio investors seemed undaunted by
whatever the results of the May 11 polls, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to an unofficial count of votes in the May 11
presidential election, the highly-controversial Vice President
Joseph Estrada has garnered at least 38 percent of the total votes
of 34 million and is heading for an irreversible victory. 
</P>
