<HEADLINE> Japan Prepares to Evacuate Japanese Nationals in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government decided
Monday to dispatch its military transport planes to Singapore to
stand by for evacuation of Japanese nationals in the riot-racked
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Two C-130H transport planes of the Air Self-Defense Force
(ASDF) will leave the Komaki air base in Aichi Prefecture, central
Japan, on Tuesday for Singapore via Manila, Japanese government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the Japanese Foreign Ministry recommended that
family members of the Japanese working in Indonesia leave the
country on fears that demonstrations to be held Wednesday on the
anniversary of an independence movement may lead to further
rioting in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are about 13,600 Japanese nationals and an
unconfirmed number of Japanese tourists in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
It will be the second time for Japan to send its military
aircraft abroad to evacuate Japanese.
</P>
<P>
Japan had been keen to send military planes overseas since a
1994 revision of the Self-Defense Forces Law under which
deployment of ASDF aircraft for evacuations became possible.
</P>
<P>
Last July, Japan sent three military transport planes to
Thailand for a possible evacuation of Japanese nationals from
Cambodia after fighting erupted between rival factions in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Japan withdrew the planes without sending them to Cambodia as
the tensions there eased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
