<HEADLINE> Hunan Lowers Prices to Stimulate Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province in central China
has announced price cuts for electricity, gas, telecommunications
and fertilizer in a bid to spur consumption.
</P>
<P>
Under the new schemes, residents and non-production enterprises
will no longer pay higher prices for the electricity they consume
in excess of the quota set by the government.
</P>
<P>
The charges for the excessive consumption of water have also
been adjusted to lower standards.
</P>
<P>
While in the past people had to pay 4.8 U.S. cents for every
cubic meter of gas exceeding the quota, the charge has been cut to
2.4 US cents in Changsha, the provincial capital. Other cities in
the province are expected to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Fees for installing the first telephone have dropped by about
40 percent in both the urban and rural areas. The price for the
second telephone will be cut by another 50 percent. In Changsha,
for example, the price for the first telephone was cut from 3,000
yuan (361 US dollars) to 1,800 yuan (217 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The province has also liberalized pricing for some varieties of
fertilizer, allowing enterprises a 10 percent price flotation
rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
