<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans Warned Against Illegal Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Lands and Agriculture
Minister Kumbirai Kangai has warned land-hungry Zimbabweans to
desist from occupying farms designated for compulsory acquisition
until the resettlement program begins.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to reports that more than 800 landless
peasants last Friday had invaded and occupied three white-owned
farms in Nyamandlovu District of West Zimbabwe, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The angry crowd Sang liberation war songs and vowed not to
move out until the government agreed to allocate them land for
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
The villagers accused the government of employing delaying
tactics in the allocation of land.
</P>
<P>
Kangai said, "people should not be occupying farms now since
the resettlement program still has to start."
</P>
<P>
He said relevant authorities in the district will deal with
the situation accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the crowd, most of them women, were clearing land
to erect dwellings.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government designated about 1,500 white farms
for land resettlement.
</P>
<P>
It is, however, uncertain that the land resettlement program
will begin in June as scheduled due to lack of funds. 
</P>
