<HEADLINE> Chinese Grain Producers Launch Rat-Killing Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Major grain-producing provinces
in China have launched operations to eradicate rats which eat or
destroy 20 million tons of crops annually in the country.
</P>
<P>
In Jilin, one of the top grain producers in northeast China's
Jilin Province, a large-scale operation has been launched on 3.6
million hectares of farmland where about 66 million rats were
killed last year.
</P>
<P>
A provincial official said the killing of millions of rats has
avoided the annual loss of more than 600,000 tons of grain, valued
at 600 million yuan (72 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In northwest China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, soldiers
also helped kill so called "big-eye" rats to safeguard grain
storage.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, scientists are engaged in a large-scale test in
Daxing County of a pharmaceutical that affects the fertility of
rats.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the popular use of the pharmaceutical, which is
non-toxic, is of great importance to grain producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
