<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economic Growth Seen to Weaken Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's overall economic
growth will weaken further this year as the impact of the regional
economic turmoil filters through the economy, the Ministry of
Trade and Industry predicted on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There remains much uncertainty over the regional political and
economic situation," the ministry said in its economic survey for
the first quarter of 1998, adding that it has retained its 1998
economic growth forecast of 2.5-4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry stressed, however, that this assumes no major
deterioration in the external environment.
</P>
<P>
It said the Singapore economy will continue to be shaped by the
disparate growth performance in the Asian, U.S. and European Union
(EU) economies.
</P>
<P>
Sectors highly exposed to regional and domestic demand will
continue to slow down while those exporting to the United States
and the EU will be supported by healthy growth in these economies,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Hence, the ministry predicted that hub services like transport
and financial services are expected to slow down further. Segments
in the commerce sector like retail, restaurants and hotels will
similarly be affected by the decline in visitor arrivals and
weaker consumer sentiments.
</P>
<P>
But, manufacturing is likely to remain generally healthy due to
strong growth in the United States and the EU, it said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, construction will be supported by public sector
projects awarded over the past two years while the communications
industry is also likely to continue enjoying healthy growth, the
ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
