<HEADLINE> L. Victoria Waters Rise, Submerging Homes, Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Lake Victoria's waters, whose
level rose last week, destroying many homes and crops, is
continuing to submerge more land in southwestern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Local residents said the volume of water in the world's second
largest fresh water lake has increased tremendously and is
spilling over into its basin from Busia in Western Province to
Migori in southern Nyanza Province.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of families in Busia, Siaya, Bondo, Nyando, Rachuonyo
and Suba districts fled their homes to escape the lake waters,
the Daily Nation newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The hardest-hit area is the flooding-prone Nyando, where
schools, homes and farms have been swallowed up by the advancing
lake, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by the Kenyan government to rescue the displaced have
been hampered by poor roads, made impassable by the floods.
</P>
<P>
The report said many of the displaced are crammed into
schools, churches and market centers in the affected region and
were in dire need of food and anti-malaria drugs.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenon was last witnessed in 1961. Some locals said it
is a result of the prevailing heavy rains but a marine expert,
Captain Joseph Mucuthi, said it is caused by the hyacinth weed
which has covered most parts of the lake.
</P>
<P>
The roots and leaves of the hyacinth and other water plants
have collected at the bottom of the lake, making it shallower,
hence the overflow, said Mucuthi.
</P>
<P>
He also attributed the increasing water volume to the
shrinking shoreline.
</P>
<P>
The shoreline, "which is now shrinking toward the lake," has
not been surveyed for more than 50 years, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
