<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africa Bracing for Information Age (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Africa, a continent marginalized
by the march of information technology in the early 1990s when
the rest of the world witnessed an unprecedented growth in
telecommunications, is striving to catch up with the galloping
world information development.
</P>
<P>
The inexorable progress toward an information-driven society,
particularly one which places heavy reliance on the electronic
exchange of information, is making telecommunications development
for all countries a matter of urgency.
</P>
<P>
"Governments across Africa are now recognizing the enormous
importance of telecommunications... and are using their political
will to implement change and upgrade their infrastructure," said
Pekka Tarjanne, secretary-general of the International
Telecommunications Union (ITU), at the just concluded Africa
Telecom 98' in Johannesburg, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
As perhaps the world's biggest potential market for improved
telecommunications, Africa represents one of the last great
opportunities for external investors.
</P>
<P>
While most of the industrialized world takes access to
telecommunications for granted, fewer than one in every 100
Africans has access to one telephone line. The figure can be as
low as two in 1,000 in sub-Saharan areas.
</P>
<P>
The International Telephone Union believes that 70 percent of
all Africans are yet to make their first telephone call. Average
waiting time for a telephone to be installed in Africa could be
as long as five years.
</P>
<P>
It's encouraging to find that some African countries have made
telecommunications a priority and are installing digital switches
with fiber optic inter-city backbones and the newest cellular and
mobile technology.
</P>
<P>
Botswana and Rwanda, for example, claim to have the world's
most sophisticated national networks, with one hundred percent of
the main lines are digital, compared with 49.5 percent in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
But at the other end of the scale, countries like Madagascar
and Uganda have highly unreliable analogue telephone systems and
poor national links between urban centers.
</P>
<P>
Most African leaders realize that the information revolution
offers Africa a dramatic opportunity to leapfrog into the future,
breaking out of decades of stagnation or decline.
</P>
<P>
One of the technology marvels is the Internet, which has
spread rapidly through Africa over the last 18 months. Two years
ago only 16 countries had full Internet access, now 47 of the 53
nations on the continent have developed some form of Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
Currently, around 700,000 people use basic Internet services,
among them, about 600,000 are in the technology-thirsty South
Africa, leaving only 100,000 among the remaining 700 million on
the continent.
</P>
<P>
This works out at about one Internet user for every 5,000
people, far below the world average, which is about one user in
every 40 people.
</P>
<P>
Along with the emerging internet services, cellular phones and
other wireless systems, funded partly by private capital, brought
a more promising solution to Africa's telecommunications needs.
</P>
<P>
Research shows that while the number of telephone services in
Africa has reached a standstill, the mobile sector has developed
over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The number of global system for mobile (GSM) communications
subscribers in Africa represents three percent of the world's GSM
users, a dramatic increase from zero three years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Bracing for Information Age (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cellular telephone services are now available in over 35
countries in Africa, mostly in the capital cities and some
major towns.
</P>
<P>
However, it is astonishing to note that there are more
cellular telephones in Thailand than in the whole African
continent, and more Internet host computers in Estonia than in
sub-Saharan Africa (excluding South Africa).
</P>
<P>
The liberalization of the sector that is occurring in some of
the countries will undoubtedly improve this situation
substantially over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Ghana, South Africa, Senegal, Morocco, Tunisia, Cote d'Ivoire
and Mauritius are among the 69 countries which had made their
commitment to open their telecoms markets to foreign companies
under a recent World Trade Organization pact.
</P>
<P>
However, in many countries, such as Ethiopia, governments
still see the telecoms sector as a very important part of their
revenue base and the public network operators are not free to
re-invest their profits in network development.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that if this continues, it may be an even
greater constraining factor than the moves to allow private
sector involvement that are now taking place.
</P>
<P>
African ministers of communications attending the Africa
Telecom 98' in Johannesburg have agreed that for the vision of
communications-based Renaissance for Africa to be materialized, a
coherent policy and regulatory framework should be developed for
the continent.
</P>
<P>
They proposed a policy framework that separated the duties of
government, regulators and operators; established independent
regulatory institutions; and that developed local communications
industries toward global competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
They are also working on programs around human resource
development, and to deal with financing and funding of
telecommunications development in Africa. The ministers have
resolved to set up an African Telecommunications Development Fund
with the aim to establish data banks in the fields of education,
agriculture, health and medicine, Internet which are identified
as very crucial building blocks for Africa's strategy into the
future.
</P>
<P>
One of the major obstacles to the development of
telecommunications in Africa is the lack of finance.
</P>
<P>
The continent attracts a mere 0.2 percent foreign investment
in telecommunications and would need eight billion Dollars if the
target of 50 million new main lines were to be laid in the next
five years so as to attain an average of one telephone line per
100 inhabitants in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, as South African President Nelson Mandela noted, the
investment needs of this rapidly expanding sector cannot be met
by the public sector alone, but through partnerships with private
sectors. Such cooperation, he believed, will promote a climate
for sustainable investment in infrastructure that guarantees good
returns and at the same time helps bridge up the information gap.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, a number of large scale telecommunication
infrastructure building projects have been announced which are
likely to substantially improve the Internet infrastructure on the
continent before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The most notable of these is AT&AMP;T's Africa One, a 1.3-
billion-U.S.-Dollar scheme which plans to encircle Africa with
39,000 kilometers of undersea fiber-optic cable that will link
countries of Africa to each other and the rest of the world. The
project, once completed, will enable 240,000 phone calls to be
made simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
An African Information Society initiative launched by the
United Nations Economic Commission for Africa, concludes in a
study: "The information revolution is one that Africa cannot
afford to miss... the price of being left out is an
insurmountable development gap between information rich and
information poor nations. If a swift response is not made the
opportunities lost will see Africa's people relegated to second
class status in the new world order." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
