<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bohai Oilfield to Produce 10 Million Tons Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bohai Oilfield near the largest
port city of Tianjin in north China has decided on a new offshore
oil development strategy that may help it boost annual production
to 10 million tons by 2005.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Shaodong, president of the China Offshore Oil
Bohai Corp. (COOBC), the Bohai Oil Field, covering 60,000 square
kilometers, has gone through 30-odd years of exploration and
development. It will be the country's first offshore oilfield to
pump more than 10 million tons of oil annually.
</P>
<P>
He explained the strategy as scientific planning and overall
development over four different oil exploration centers within the
Bohai Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The four are: the Liaobei oil exploration center, consisting of
the Jinzhou 20-2 and Jinzhou 9-3 oilfields; the Liaozhong center,
based on Suizhong 36-1; the Shijiuzhai center, based on
Qinhuangdao 32-6 oilfield.
</P>
<P>
Exploration activities in recent years have proven that the
Bohai Gulf abounds in oil and gas resources, with geological oil
reserves topping 800 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The Suizhong 36-1 and Qinhuangdao 32-6 oilfields in the Bohai
Gulf are the country's largest offshore oilfields, each with oil
reserves exceeding 100 million tons.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Bohai will use different oil
exploration and development methods according to the conditions in
the four centers to meet its goals, mainly including exploration
across both onshore and offshore, fast drilling, and joint
exploration by linking pipelines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Encourage Children to Go out and Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Parents should encourage
children to go out and play for an hour to several hours every
day, according to the first physical activity guideline drawn
specifically for elementary school-age children in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
"Children who enjoy expending calories when they are young are
more likely to do so later in life," recommended the National
Association for Sport and Physical Education (NASPE) in a report
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Those who are inactive as kids are likely to be slugs when they
get older, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Judith Young, executive director of the NASPE, a professional
group of physical education teachers, coaches, and exercise
scientists, said that parents who keep their children heavily
scheduled with organized sedentary activities such as piano or
computer lessons ought to adjust their priorities to make physical
activities part of children's life.
</P>
<P>
The report encourages children to get more variety than regular
routine of walking, running and weight-training skills
characterized by much adult exercise.
</P>
<P>
Most of children's time should be in activities such as
climbing, tumbling and other things that have few rules and little
formal organization, the NASPE recommended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urged to Promote Forest Products Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Primary Industries
Minister Lim Keng Yaik appealed to ASEAN countries Monday to
cooperate closely in market promotion for forest products in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Opening the first meeting of ASEAN senior officials on forestry
here, Lim said individual countries of ASEAN might be competing
for the same export markets for tropical timber products. "But
considering the numerous problems we face, it is not difficult to
recognize the usefulness and necessity for member countries to
pool resources for mutual benefits."
</P>
<P>
The nine-member grouping should adopt export-oriented policies
and produce better quality forest products to counter competition
from the Pacific islands, Africa and South America as well as
temperate hardwood and softwood, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN should source more from each other and welcome the
proposed mechanism of bilateral payment arrangement, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, a major tropical forest region in the world with forest
covering some 180 million hectares or 60 percent of the land area,
 is the most important supplier of tropical timber products in the
world, accounting for more than 70 percent of the international
trade of these products valued at more than 15 billion U.S.
dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Lim said the grouping has thus far been able to withstand
several attempts to discredit tropical timber by way of adopting
common positions on international forestry and timber issues.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials at the three-day meeting will discuss mainly
an ASEAN Vision Statement on Forestry, in particular the
cooperative efforts and a strategic action plan for consideration
by the Sixth ASEAN Summit to be held in Hanoi in December.
</P>
<P>
The officials are expected to discuss flagship projects which
will be initiated by particular member countries.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
