<HEADLINE> Cambodians Begin Voter Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Cambodians began Monday to head
for the Buddhist temples and schools, voter registration centers
for the general election scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
Registration opened about 7:00 a.m. local time and would last
28 days to June 15.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, with a population of 10.45 million, has 5.43 million
eligible voters who will elect 122 parliament members in the
election.
</P>
<P>
The number of registration of the first day was lower than
expected, maybe because of rain, or lacking of media propaganda,
with many still didn't know which centers would be operating.
</P>
<P>
However electoral officials said there were reports of
equipment failures and shortages of registration materials that
could have caused the low registration.
</P>
<P>
"It is very difficult for us, but we will do our best to
resolve the problems," they said.
</P>
<P>
The election, the second general election since 1993, is
estimated to cost more than 26 million U.S. dollars, for which the
international community will pay for at least 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's 1993 election organized and supervised by U.N. cost
tow billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
