<HEADLINE> Chinese Public Invited to Choose Names for Four Baby Tigers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A hot-line telephone in the Beijing
Zoo has been ringing off the hook with enthusiastic citizens
calling in to choose names for four baby Manchurian tigers.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 200 names have been proposed for the four
baby tigers, which were born on May 1 in the zoo, according to
Zhang Jinguo, vice-director of the zoo.
</P>
<P>
The mother tiger, named Jisheng, has become the heroin of the
zoo. Since 1993, Jisheng has given birth to 18 babies, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The number of Manchurian Tigers has decreased sharply in recent
years, and the endangered animal has been put under state
first-class protection.
</P>
<P>
"This year is the year of the tiger according to China's lunar
calendar," said Zhang, adding that, "Choosing a name may help
raise public awareness of protecting the animal."
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the phone calls were from not only Beijing but also
cities in other provinces. The zoo has set up a name-selection
committee. The four winning names will be announced on May 20.
</P>
<P>
Since 1956, the Beijing Zoo has artificially propagated more
than 100 tigers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
