<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economy Grows by 5.6 PCT in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore economy grew by 5.6
percent in the first quarter of this year, the Ministry of Trade
and Industry said on Monday as it released the Economic Survey of
Singapore for the first quarter 1998.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter economic survey showed that the
manufacturing, construction and financial &AMP; business services
sectors all turned in moderately healthy growth on a year-on-year
basis.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, the regional economic slowdown has begun to
bite, with growth momentum slowing in the first three months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
All sectors showed weaker year-on-year growth, as compared to
the previous quarter, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
It said that manufacturing output rose by 6.1 percent, partly
due to the low base in the first quarter 1997, and partly because
of the strong growth in the chemical and transport equipment
industries.
</P>
<P>
The electronics industry increased by 4.6 percent, with strong
growth in semi-conductors, printers and printed circuit board
assemblies.
</P>
<P>
The financial &AMP; business services sector expanded by 6.3
percent, down from 9.6 percent a quarter earlier. Growth in
financial services was dragged down by a slowdown in regional
financing and a tapering off in volatility in the foreign exchange
markets.
</P>
<P>
The commerce sector saw a significant slowing in growth
momentum in the first quarter of the year as consumption demand,
both external and domestic, moderated. Overall sectoral growth was
a sluggish 1.2 percent in the first three months, down from the
3.2 percent a quarter earlier.
</P>
<P>
Growth in transport and communications moderated to 6.1
percent, on the back of the continued slowdown in trade and
economic growth in the region, the survey said. It added, however,
that the communications sub-sector remained healthy, supported
mainly by increased competition in the mobile communications
segment.
</P>
<P>
The construction sector continued to turn in double-digit
growth of 11 percent. Construction activity remained healthy,
given the strong pipeline in recent years, it said, pointing out
that public-sector residential building and civil engineering work
supported the growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
