<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jakarta's Massive Riots Cause Huge Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government said that
losses from damaged property alone in last week's rioting in the
capital of Jakarta were estimated at 2.5 trillion rupiah (250
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The estimation was made by Coordinating Minister for Economy,
Finance and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita here Sunday night
after an inspection of several riot-affected areas in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Material losses throughout the country could be billions of
dollars, local leading newspapers Monday quoted the minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jakarta Governor Sutiyoso said the three days of
rioting from last Wednesday to Friday in the city had left 4,940
buildings damaged, burned down or looted. They included 4,204
shops, shopping malls, restaurants, automobile workshops and more
than 500 bank offices.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, 1,026 houses were either looted or
damaged, two churches were burned down, 1,120 cars and 821
motorbikes were set ablaze and almost 520 street lights and
traffic lights were damaged.
</P>
<P>
He said the 2.5-trillion-rupiah property loss is 40 percent
higher than the city's budget for this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Sjahri Sabirin, governor of Bank Indonesia, the central bank,
also said 534 bank offices belonging to 64 banks throughout the
country, including 501 in Greater Jakarta, and 220 automatic
teller machines were damaged or looted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, State Distribution Agency (Bulog) chief Beddu Amang
said that 500 tons of rice and 1,800 tons of sugar worth 4.24
billion rupiah (about 450,000 U.S. dollars) owned by his agency
had been looted.
</P>
<P>
Calmness and order returned to Jakarta in the last two days
amid heavy military presence. However, most supermarkets and
restaurants remained closed.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta military command deployed thousands of armed
soldiers to guard the city as tanks and armored vehicles rolled
through city streets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
