<HEADLINE> Thai Trade With Neighbors on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's trade with its four
neighbors in the first four months this year increased by 138
percent from that of the same period last year to 62.89 billion
baht (1.66 billion U.S. dollars), the Bangkok Post Monday quoted
Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Supachai, also Commerce Minister, the value of
Thai exports to Malaysia, Laos, Cambodia and Myanmar from January
to April totaled 50.23 billion baht (1.32 billion dollars), up by
146.6 percent, leaving a trade surplus of 37.57 billion baht (989
million dollars), a 161.5 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Trade with Malaysia increased by 217 percent, while that with
Laos and Cambodia jumped by 29 percent and 0.4 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, border trade with Myanmar dropped by 23 percent due to
security problems.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said Thailand would meet Myanmar officials in
September to solve the problems including checkpoints, customs and
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said a committee in charge of border trade will also
streamline the complicated procedures involving eight departments
at present.
</P>
<P>
The committee recommended that the Customs Department should
take charge of all border trade and provide one-stop service for
importers and exporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
