<HEADLINE> Myanmar Forms Computer Associations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Two Myanmar associations of computer
technicians and entrepreneurs have been formed here to promote the
development and advancement of computer technology in the country.
</P>
<P>
The associations, each with 19 members, were established on
</P>
<P>
Sunday, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, a CD on "Myanmar Another Incarnation," the
first interactive one on various aspects of Myanmar and created by
young technicians of the Cooperative Stores Syndicate (CSS), was
launched in the capital, signifying an important step in the
progress of computer technology in the country.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are being made to create CDs on Tipitaka, the heritage
of Myanmar Buddhism, according to the CSS.
</P>
<P>
The CSS has trained nearly 3,000 young Myanmar technicians
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar started computerized teaching at basic education
schools in 1993, and the number of computers used in teaching
increased from the then 64 to 3,000 in schools, universities and
institutes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar promulgated its Computer Technology Development Law in
September 1996. 
</P>
