<HEADLINE> Liaoning Province Standardizing Reform Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has been trying to develop a modern enterprise system in
a more standardized way.
</P>
<P>
A recent study of 126 companies chosen to try out the modern
enterprises system showed that 84 have incorporated or issued
shares or become state-backed corporations, but the other 42 have
made no changes.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three percent of them have share holders meetings, 60
percent have boards of directors, and 56 percent have supervisory
councils.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning became an old industrial center in the early years
after the founding of New China and is still the home of a tenth
of the country's state-owned enterprises. The central government
approved experiments there in the introduction of a modern
enterprise system in 1994, and 128 companies have been put on the
experiment list. 
</P>
