<HEADLINE> CEPAL: Efficiency, Transparency in Public Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Economic Commission for
Latin America and Caribbean (CEPAL) ended on Saturday its 27th
session in Oranjestad, Aruba, calling for efficiency and
transparency in the region's public finance.
</P>
<P>
According to a CEPAL press release, the session approved the
Aruba Declaration after a six-day discussion on the role of public
finance in the region's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Aruba Declaration supported CEPAL's proposal on
strengthening government's role in social and economic life and on
raising efficiency and transparency of the public finance.
</P>
<P>
The session examined the effect of the Asian financial crisis
on the region's economy and its population.
</P>
<P>
The session also adopted a proposal on CEPAL's reform, its
working programs for the next two years, and ways to eliminate
poverty in the area, and to promote development and technology
cooperation among countries.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 41 CEPAL member countries attended the
session which opened on May 11.
</P>
<P>
With its headquarters in Santiago, CEPAL holds its sessions
every two years with the next one to be held in Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
