<HEADLINE> Thailand's Imports of Luxury Goods Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand saw a sharp fall in luxury
goods imports during the first two months this year compared with
December 1997 and the same period of the previous year, the Nation
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Finance Ministry, imports of 17 luxury goods
categories in January this year totaled 25.61 billion U.S.
dollars, down 14 percent from December 1997 and 68.86 percent from
January 1997.
</P>
<P>
The top six import items in January this year were cameras and
accessories, liquor and spirits, perfumes and cosmetics, fruits,
watches and accessories and optical lenses.
</P>
<P>
As for February, the imports of the 17 categories of luxury
products were up 10 percent from the previous month but down 48.26
percent from the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has launched campaigns such as "Thais-Help-Thais" and
"Do It Right for Thailand" in a bid to encourage people to buy
domestic products to reduce the foreign currencies outflow caused
by importing luxury goods.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government also raised import duties on luxury goods
in February this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Pioneer Earthquake Prediction (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Several years of experimentation have shown that the method is
particularly suitable for forecasting earthquakes in island and
coastal areas. Out of the 34 successful predictions made between
January 1990 and May 1997, 11 were of quakes which occurred in
Taiwan, eight in Japan and four in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Qiang further explained that a large quantity of a kind of
hydrate, which is made up of a methane molecule and five water
molecules, exists 200 m to 300 m under the surface of the
ocean. The increasing stress force before the earthquake may cause
the hydrate to release large quantities of methane gas and form a
low-lying cloud, and this may lead to a sharp increase of
temperature.
</P>
<P>
Qiang said that he believes that an anomalous temperature rise
which is not caused by meteorological factors is the precursor of
an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, clouds may obscure this and cause
difficulties for prediction.
</P>
<P>
A quake measuring 6.2 on the Richter Scale jolted Zhangjiakou
Prefecture in northern China's Hebei Province on January 10 this
year. The quake was not predicted because the area was overcast
for several days before the quake, Qiang explained.
</P>
<P>
But this may be overcome by using microwave remote-sensing
technology, said Qiang, adding that China is designing a system of
seven small satellites for this purpose, equipped with microwave
radiometers.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Robert K. Vincent of the Department of Geology of Bowling
Green State University, Ohio, has introduced the earthquake
prediction method developed by Qiang Zuji and Dian Changgong in
his newly published textbook, "Fundamentals of Geological and
Environmental Remote Sensing."
</P>
<P>
Vincent says that the technology is compelling enough to be
included in his book because of its potential for being one of the
greatest contributions that remote sensing can make to mankind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
