<HEADLINE> El Nino-Related Forest Fires Taking Heavy Toll in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 50 people have died
fighting forest fires in Mexico so far this year, which is hit by
a record low rainfall because of the El Nino weather phenomenon,
official reports said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
With rainfall at one tenth of average levels, Mexico is plagued
by its worst drought in 70 years, said Environment Minister Julia
Carabias following a visit on Saturday to the southern state of
Chiapas, where raging blazes have turned it to a disaster area.
</P>
<P>
At least six people, including five firefighters, were killed
battling fires in two states on Saturday, bring the toll to close
to 50 this year, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,500 firefighters were trying to check a deadly fire
burning ancient rainforests in southern Oaxaca state, home to
thousands of rare species of plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
According to La Jornada newspaper, 25 million acres (10 million
hectares) of farm land in Mexico have already been lost to the
drought and the government will have to increase imports of basic
grains by 12 to 17 percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
