<DOCNO> XIE19980518.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Pioneer Earthquake Prediction Technology (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The dream of many scientists to
accurately predict earthquakes several days in advance will come
true in a foreseeable future, thanks to the joint efforts of
Chinese seismologists, meteorologists and their colleagues in
other branches of science.
</P>
<P>
Two recent quakes, which hit Okinawa in Japan and Tangshan City
in northern China on May 4 and April 14, respectively, were
successfully predicted by a group of Chinese scientists who
employed a thermal infrared remote-sensing method using a satellite.
</P>
<P>
A thesis on this subject written by Qiang Zuji, Dian
Changgong and Li Lingzhi, researchers at the Satellite Prediction
Research Center for Natural Disasters under the China Aerospace
Corporation, will be published in the latest issue of the
journal China Science.
</P>
<P>
From 1990 to 1997 a total of 80 predictions were made, of which
41 were accurate in terms of time, location and magnitude,
according to professor Qiang, "And the accuracy is increasing."
</P>
<P>
Writing in the US journal Science last year, several US
seismologists said that it was impossible to predict earthquakes
accurately with the present technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
However, Chinese scientists believe that satellite thermal
infrared technology, combined with technologies borrowed from
other branches of learning, can bring new accuracy to earthquake
prediction.
</P>
<P>
Qiang, who earned his master's degree in the late 1950s in the
former Soviet Union and has been studying earthquakes for decades,
explained that before an earthquake strikes, local rock formations
are under great pressure, and cracks may appear around the quake
center, releasing carbon dioxide, hydrogen, nitrogen and methane.
</P>
<P>
These gases may release thermal energy and produce thermal
infrared anomalies, said Qiang.
</P>
<P>
This phenomenon can be detected with satellite remote sensing
technology. Then, combined with research on geological structures,
the distribution of quake belts, and other meteorological data,
the time, location of the epicenter and magnitude of the quake can
be predicted, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
