<HEADLINE> Annan: Think of Cutting-Across-Frontiers Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan reminded American students that too many people are still
thinking about international issues "in local terms, constrained
by boundaries."
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks Sunday at Macalester College in St. Paul,
Minnesota, where he was to receive an honorary degree.
</P>
<P>
He said issues in the face of the 185-member-state United
Nations such as environment, drugs, pandemics, sustainable
development are all issues cutting across all frontiers.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the challenges of our age are problems without
passports; to address them we need blueprints without borders. The
United Nations is there to provide them."
</P>
<P>
"And yet, this same United Nations is undergoing a financial
crisis, the unpaid dues owed by the United States amounts to 1.6
billion U.S. dollars. While this is a critical sum for the United
Nations, it's slightly less than the money Titanic has made around
the world in a matter of months."
</P>
<P>
"Reflect for a moment on what 1.6 billion dollars actually
means to a great country like yours. On a per capita basis, it
represents just over six dollars per American to repay a debt
built up over a decade."
</P>
<P>
"That amount would not buy you a pitcher of beer at O'Garea's."
</P>
<P>
Annan completed his studies in economics at the college in 1961
when he was 23, following his studies at the University of Science
and Technology at Kumasi, Ghana, his home country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
