<HEADLINE> North Chinese Province Opening Property Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
has decided to start a secondary property market in the latter
half of the year for government-subsidized apartments bought by
employees of state-owned enterprises or institutions.
</P>
<P>
Local sources say that provincial authorities have been working
hard to come up with ways to standardize trade on the secondary
market and they will start by halting the practice of distributing
apartments as a welfare form.
</P>
<P>
The province will use special construction funds of different
institutions for the housing market and provide subsidies to
workers to cover the expense of buying their own apartments and
for repaying housing loans.
</P>
<P>
Various departments, state-owned enterprises, and institutions
will have to sell newly-built apartments and vacant flats at cost,
the sources say.
</P>
<P>
By July 1, the cumulative public housing fund is expected to be
enough to cover all employees of state-owned or collectively-owned
enterprises. State banks will also provide apartments loans in
medium-sized or larger cities.
</P>
<P>
Hebei has increased its original investment for housing this
year to 15 billion yuan and it expects to add 20 million sq m of
apartments this year.
</P>
<P>
It will also try to improve 5 million sq.m. of old apartments
to add to the market.
</P>
<P>
It will also build apartments for low-income families and ask
developers to sell vacant flats at reduced prices and get rid of
various extra charges in housing construction to keep costs
down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
