<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low-cost Desktop PC Market to Balloon --Analysis Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Low-cost personal computers,
which touched off a price war in the U.S PC industry last year,
may gain large share in the U.S. as well as global PC market.
</P>
<P>
Computers pricing at around 1,000 U.S. dollars will account for
a quarter of global desktop PC unit shipments by 2001, a U.S.
firm, which provides information technology data, analysis and
consulting, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, low-cost PCs had a standing of 12 percent globally.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, said International Development
Corporation (IDC), a commercial transition to lower price points
will help the low-cost category maintain the growth momentum
established over the past year, with sub-1,000-dollar unit
shipments swelling to over a third of the market in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Falling component prices, vendor price aggression and the rise
of Internet are the key factors that led to the enthusiastic
reception and rapid adoption of low cost desktops. IDC said that
these factors will continue to drive the market for
sub-1,000-dollar systems. Increased pressure on component
manufacturers to reduce cost and continued market share
consolidation among the top PC vendors will accelerate the shift
among commercial and consumer buyers alike over the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
Although continued price erosion puts increasing pressure on PC
companies and component vendors, users will benefit from gains
both from even lower prices as well as more robust configurations
at existing price points. Advancing technology will allow for more
function integration and software implementation for key
sub-systems, enabling feature-rich, capable systems at prices even
lower than today's.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, another market analysis company, Dataquest, said that
today's battles in the PC industry will serve to push technology
and marketing campaigns further in the future. The outcome will
be a positive total computer systems market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
