<HEADLINE> U.S. Holds Air-Show to Celebrate Armed Forces Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense Department held
a two-day air-show at the Andrews Air Force Base, Maryland, during
the weekend to celebrate the nation's Armed Force Day.
</P>
<P>
The 40th annual Department of Defense Joint Services Open House
featured with military demonstrations including the Navy's Blue
Angels, flying their high-performance F-18 Hornets, and the U.S.
Army's Parachute Team, the Golden Knights, as well as exhibitions
of newest weapon systems.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force demonstrated the B-1B bomber, F-15 fighter and
C-130 cargo aircraft. In addition, the F-17 stealth fighter, B-52,
E-3 airborne warning and control system, KC-10 tanker and C-17 and
C-5 aircraft were on display and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
A special attraction was the Air Force One, a C-137 aircraft
known as Special Air Mission 26000 that served every American
President since John F. Kennedy. The plane, retired in March, was
open to public during the two-day Open House. It is going to be
set up as a permanent static display at the Air Force Museum in
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
The Navy showed its F/A-18F Super Hornet, F-14 Tomcat, S-3
Viking, F/A-18C Hornet and E-2 Hawkeye. The Marine Corps displayed
made an aerial demonstration of the capability of the AV-8B
Harrier, as well as static displays of the Corps' AH-1W attack
helicopter, CH-53E heavy-lift helicopter, Light Armored Vehicle,
M198 howitzer, and the Corps' new Advanced Amphibious Assault
Vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Army demonstrated its newest weapon system,
the Crusador Field Artillery System, and the Cost Guard displayed
its rescue aircraft and other equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
